        `,
        'Ahom': 'Ahom differentiates open vowels (not followed by a consonant) and closed vowels (followed by a consonant). Aksharamukha performs this automatically by choosing the appropriate forms. Thus, /ahoá¹ƒ/ is rightly rendered as <span class="ahom">ğ‘œ’ğ‘œ‘ğ‘œªğ‘œ¨</span> rather than <span class="ahom">ğ‘œ’ğ‘œ‘ğ‘œ¦ğ‘œªğ‘œ¡</span>. We outline the relevant open/closed vowels below. <br/><br/> <i>Open:</i> ki kÄ« ku kÅ« ke ko : <span class="ahom">ğ‘œ€ğ‘œ£ ğ‘œ€ğ‘œ£ ğ‘œ€ğ‘œ¥ ğ‘œ€ğ‘œ¥ ğ‘œ€ğ‘œ¦ğ‘œ§ ğ‘œ€ğ‘œ¦ğ‘œ¡</span><br/> <i>Closed:</i> kik kÄ«k kuk kÅ«k kek kok : <span class="ahom">ğ‘œ€ğ‘œ¢ğ‘œ€ğ‘œ« ğ‘œ€ğ‘œ¢ğ‘œ€ğ‘œ« ğ‘œ€ğ‘œ¤ğ‘œ€ğ‘œ« ğ‘œ€ğ‘œ¤ğ‘œ€ğ‘œ« ğ‘œ€ğ‘œ¦ğ‘œ€ğ‘œ« ğ‘œ€ğ‘œ¨ğ‘œ€ğ‘œ«</span><br/><i>With Anusvara:</i> kiá¹ƒ kÄ«á¹ƒ kuá¹ƒ kÅ«á¹ƒ keá¹ƒ koá¹ƒ : <span class="ahom">ğ‘œ€ğ‘œªğ‘œ¢ ğ‘œ€ğ‘œªğ‘œ¢ ğ‘œ€ğ‘œªğ‘œ¤ ğ‘œ€ğ‘œªğ‘œ¤ ğ‘œ€ğ‘œªğ‘œ§ ğ‘œ€ğ‘œªğ‘œ¨</span><br/><br/> This can be disabled by choosing the <i>Preserve Source</i> option. <br/><br/> <b>Extended Ahom</b><br/> There is a <a href="https://www.scribd.com/document/411696990/Tai-%C4%80hom-Script-P%C4%81%C4%BCi">publication</a> that uses additional extended letters, namely <i>á¹­a, á¹­ha, á¸a, á¸ha, á¹‡a & va</i>, to print the Pali Tripitaka in the Ahom script. These characters are not available in Unicode yet and, hence, cannot be used as of now.',
        'HanifiRohingya': 'Aksharamukha handles the Rohingya specific characters in the following way. <ul><li>The tones have been mapped to long vowels. The short high tone is unmarked, the long falling tone is marked with \\ and the long rising tone marked with / <br/> <span class="hanifirohingya"> ğ´‘ğ´ğ´¤ ğ´‘ğ´ğ´¥ ğ´‘ğ´ğ´¦</span> : kÄ kÄ\\ kÄ/ <li>Sakin (denoting a bare consonant) is marked using ; <li> Geminations are automatically shown using the Tossa <br/> /dda/ : <span class="hanifirohingya">ğ´Šğ´§ğ´</span>. <li> Kinna /wa/ and Kinna /ya/   with vowels shown as /i/ and /u/<li> Kinna /wa/ and Kinna /ya/  with consonants shown as /y/ and /v/ with Nukta i.e yÌˆ & vÌˆ (in IAST)</ul>',
        'MasaramGondi': 'Repha and the Ra-kara are formed by default. /kra/ and /rka/ become <span class="masaramgondi">ğ‘´Œğ‘µ‡</span> and <span class="masaramgondi">ğ‘µ†ğ‘´Œ</span> automatically',
        'Mongolian': 'The mapping for the Ali Gali orthography for Mongolian was referenced from the Wikipedia article. The mapping is not yet verified. If you have any feedback on the mapping, forms of the letters used and an appropriate font that could be used, please send it to vinodh@virtualvinodh.com',
        'GunjalaGondi': 'Gunjala Gondi does not have an explicit visible Virama. It also lacks /Ã±/ and /á¹‡/. When these phonemes occur in their vowelless forms to nasalize their corresponding consonant series, they are replaced by the Anusvara.',
        'Soyombo': 'The Sanskrit phonemes /c/, /ch/ & /j/ are mapped to consonants TSA, TSHA & DZA respectively (according to Tibetan conventions). This can be changed by selecting the <i>Use Sanskrit palatals</i> options, which will use the Sanskrit-specific consonants.<br/><br/> Aksharamukha by default uses Sanskrit-specific orthography. However, Mongolian/Tibetan specific orthographic practices can be enabled as required. <ul> <li> Use final letters to encode word-final vowelless consonants <br/> samyak asmad : <span class="soyombo">ğ‘ªğ‘©´ğ‘ª™ğ‘©»ğ‘ª‹ ğ‘©ğ‘ªğ‘ª™ğ‘©´ğ‘ª</span> <br/> There are final forms for 11 consonants. <br/> ak ag aá¹… ad an ab am ar al aÅ› as : <span class="soyombo">ğ‘©ğ‘ª‹ ğ‘©ğ‘ªŠ ğ‘©ğ‘ªŒ ğ‘©ğ‘ª ğ‘©ğ‘ª ğ‘©ğ‘ª ğ‘©ğ‘ª ğ‘©ğ‘ª‘ ğ‘©ğ‘ª’ ğ‘©ğ‘ª“ ğ‘©ğ‘ª”</span><li> Use initial-forms for /ra/, /la/ and /sa/. <br/> rka lka ska : <span class="soyombo">ğ‘ª†ğ‘©œ ğ‘ª‡ğ‘©œ ğ‘ª‰ğ‘©œ</span> (Tibetan) : <span class="soyombo">ğ‘©¼ğ‘ª™ğ‘©œ ğ‘©½ğ‘ª™ğ‘©œ ğ‘ªğ‘ª™ğ‘©œ</span> (Sanskrit) <li> Convert spaces into Tshegs. pra co da yÄt :  <span class="soyombo">ğ‘©°ğ‘ª™ğ‘©¼ğ‘ªšğ‘©µğ‘©–ğ‘ªšğ‘©­ğ‘ªšğ‘©»ğ‘©›ğ‘©«</span></ul> Since, Soyombo does not have a visible Virama, certain Sanskrit words that do end in a consonants cannot be accurately expressed (and has to be contextually inferrred). One way to overcome this is to use Tshegs and divide the word into indidvidual syllables (similar to Tibetan). /parama/ as <span class="soyombo">ğ‘©°ğ‘ªšğ‘©¼ğ‘ªšğ‘©´</span> (pa^ra^ma) but /param/ as <span class="soyombo">ğ‘©°ğ‘ªšğ‘©¼ğ‘©´</span> (pa^rama). Or alternatively use Mongolian-final forms. /param/ as <span class="soyombo">ğ‘©°ğ‘©¼ğ‘ª</span>.',
        'KhomThai': 'The font used encodes Khom Thai using Thai Unicode characters. In the absence of the font, the text will appear as plain Thai. The font is also specifically aimed for only Pali, therefore, it misses Sanskrit-specific characters that include the independent vowels of /á¹›/, /á¹/, /á¸·/, /á¸¹/, /ai/ and /au/, the dependent vowel signs /á¸·/, /á¸¹/ and /au/ and the consonants /Å›/ and /á¹£/. They have been approximated to closest possible letter. Traditionally, Khom Thai can express both Sanskrit and Pali.',
        'Mon': 'The Sanskrit characters /á¹›/, /á¹/, /á¸·/,  /á¸¹/, /Å›/ and /á¹£/ were directly adopted from the corresponding Burmese characters for the sake of completing the Indic character reportoire.',
        'Shan': 'The Sanskrit characters /á¹›/, /á¹/, /á¸·/,  /á¸¹/, /Å›/ and /á¹£/ were directly adopted from the corresponding Burmese characters for the sake of completing the Indic character reportoire.',
        'KhamtiShan': '<b>Numerals</b><br/> Khamti in India use Myanmar numerals instead of Shan numerals. This can be enabled if needed <br/><br/> <b> Khamti /r/ </b><br/> Khamti also has an archaic /r/ <span class="khamtishan">ê©³</span>. An option can be enabled to use this instead of <span class="khamtishan">á€›</span>.',
        'TaiLaing': '',
        'ZanabazarSquare': 'The Sanskrit phonemes /c/, /ch/ & /j/ are mapped to consonants TSA, TSHA, & DZA respectively (according to Tibetan conventions). This can be changed by selecting the <i>Use Sanskrit palatals options</i>, which will use the Sanskrit-specific consonants <span class="zanabazarsquare">ğ‘¨ ğ‘¨‘ ğ‘¨’</span> instead of <span class="zanabazarsquare">ğ‘¨£ ğ‘¨¤ ğ‘¨¥</span>.<br/><br/> Aksharamukha by default uses Sanskrit-specific orthography. However, Mongolian/Tibetan specific orthographic practices can be enabled as required. <ul> <li>Tibetan uses contextual alternatives for post-consonantal /ya/, /ra/, /la/ and /va/, while Sanskrit does not. <br/> kya kra kla kva: <span class="zanabazarsquare">ğ‘¨‹ğ‘©‡ğ‘¨ª ğ‘¨‹ğ‘©‡ğ‘¨« ğ‘¨‹ğ‘©‡ğ‘¨¬ ğ‘¨‹ğ‘©‡ğ‘¨­ </span> (Sanskrit) : <span class="zanabazarsquare">ğ‘¨‹ğ‘¨» ğ‘¨‹ğ‘¨¼ ğ‘¨‹ğ‘¨½ ğ‘¨‹ğ‘¨¾ </span> (Tibetan) <li>The Tibetan orthography employs a repha-like character for pre-consonantal /ra/. <br/> rka : <span class="zanabazarsquare">ğ‘¨«ğ‘©‡ğ‘¨‹</span> (Sanskrit) : <span class="zanabazarsquare">ğ‘¨ºğ‘¨‹</span> (Tibetan)<li> Sanskrit orthography also uses different signs for /ai/ and /au/ as opposed to Mongolian. <br/>ai au kai kau : <span class="zanabazarsquare">ğ‘¨€ğ‘¨„ğ‘¨Š ğ‘¨€ğ‘¨†ğ‘¨Š ğ‘¨‹ğ‘¨„ğ‘¨Š ğ‘¨‹ğ‘¨†ğ‘¨Š</span> (Sanskrit) : <span class="zanabazarsquare">ğ‘¨€ğ‘¨‡ ğ‘¨€ğ‘¨ˆ ğ‘¨‹ğ‘¨‡ ğ‘¨‹ğ‘¨ˆ</span> (Mongolian) <li> Mongolian orthography uses a dot to suppress the inherent vowel instead of a Virama. <br/>ak: <span class="zanabazarsquare">ğ‘¨€ğ‘¨¬ğ‘¨³</span> (Mongolian) : <span class="zanabazarsquare">ğ‘¨€ğ‘¨¬ğ‘¨´</span> (Tibetan/Sanskrit) <li> Convert spaces into Tshegs. pra co da yÄt : <span class="zanabazarsquare">ğ‘¨ğ‘©‡ğ‘¨«ğ‘©ğ‘¨£ğ‘¨†ğ‘©ğ‘¨›ğ‘©ğ‘¨ªğ‘¨Šğ‘¨™ğ‘¨´</span> </ul> These alternate forms can be chosen by selecting the appropriate checkboxes in the ouput section.',
        'Avestan': 'Avestan has a tradition of being transliterated into Gujarati and Devanagari. This has been followed more or less. As such, Avestan fricatives have been mapped to Indian aspirates. Avestan vowels that do not have Indic equivalents have been mapped to /Ã¦/, /Ç£/ and /Ã´/. <span class="avestan">ğ¬ƒ</span> is mapped to /Ä_o/. There are additional Avestan consonants that do not fit into the Indic scheme above. In such cases, they are mapped to the the closest Nukta-ted Indic counterparts. <span class="avestan">ğ¬ ğ¬¡ ğ¬¤ ğ¬²</span> (right to left) :  tÌˆ vÌˆ á¹…Ìˆ zÌˆ (left to right).<br/><br/>At non-initial positions /ya/ is represented by <span class="avestan">ğ¬Œğ¬Œ</span>. Similarly, at non-initial positions, /va/ is represented by <span class="avestan">ğ¬ğ¬</span>. And, /Äá¹ƒ/ becomes <span class="avestan">ğ¬…</span><br/><br/><b> Nativization Conventions </b> <br/><br/>The following nativization conventions are automatically applied to the Avestan output in accordance to the Avestan orthographic conventions. <br/> <ul><li>Contextual placement of <span class="avestan">ğ¬ ğ¬² ğ¬§</span><li>/kh/ and /Å›/ before /y/ are replaced by the palatalized <span class="avestan">ğ¬’ ğ¬³</span> respectively.</ul> ',
        'Balinese': 'Aksharamukha places the repha automatically on the preceding consonants. /karma/ : <span class="balinese">á¬“á¬ƒá¬«</span>',
        'Assamese': 'Khanda /ta/ is formed automatically depending on the text. It is used word-finally and at positions where /t/ does not form conjoining conjuncts. /tat/ : <span class="bengali">à¦¤à§</span> & /utpÄda/ : <span class="bengali">à¦‰à§à¦ªà¦¦</span> but /atthi/ : <span class="bengali">à¦…à¦¤à§à¦¥à¦¿</span>.  <br/><br/><b> Nativization Conventions </b> <br/><br/>The following nativization conventions are automatically applied to the Assamese output to increase readability. <br/> <ul> <li> /va/ is replaced by /ba/. <li> /y/ and /áº/ are contextually placed based on the following rules. /y/ is used word-intially and at post-consonantal positions. Otherise, /áº/ is used.</ul>',
        'Bengali': '<span class="bengali">à§±</span> is actually an Assamese letter that the converter uses to represent /va/. Bengali script does not contain /va/ in in its native reportoire. Khanda /ta/ is formed automatically depending on the text. It is used word-finally and at positions where /t/ does not form conjoining conjuncts. /tat/ : <span class="bengali">à¦¤à§</span> & /utpÄda/ : <span class="bengali">à¦‰à§à¦ªà¦¦</span> but /atthi/ : <span class="bengali">à¦…à¦¤à§à¦¥à¦¿</span>.  <br/><br/><b> Nativization Conventions </b> <br/><br/>The following nativization conventions are automatically applied to the Bengali output to increase readability. <br/> <ul> <li> /va/ is replaced by /ba/. <li> /y/ and /áº/ are contextually placed based on the following rules. /y/ is used word-intially and at post-consonantal positions. Otherise, /áº/ is used at intervocalic positions.</ul>',
        'Burmese': 'The following are automatically applied to the output text. <ul> <li> Tall /Ä/ is automatically used according to the preceding consonant. /kÄ/ : <span class="burmese">á€€á€¬</span> but /gÄ/ : <span class="burmese">á€‚á€«</span> <li> Kinzi is formed automatically. /saá¹…ghaá¸¥/ : <span class="burmese">á€á€„á€ºá€¹á€ƒá€¸</span> <li> Repha is similarly formed automatically. /dharma/ : <span class="burmese">á€“á€›á€ºá€¹á€™</span><li>/ssa/ and /Ã±Ã±a/ are rendered as <span class="burmese">á€¿</span> and <span class="burmese">á€Š</span> respectively</ul>',
        'Chakma': 'Modern Chakma uses only few restricted conjunct sequences and others are rendered using a visible Virama. However, you can enable an option to use all possible conjuncts.  In accordance with Chakma orthography, the explicit Virama (Maayaa) is used to geminate consonants e.g. <span class="chakma">ğ‘„‡ğ‘„¨ğ‘„–ğ‘„´ğ‘„³ğ‘„ ğ‘„¬ </span>: kittáºe.  <br/><br/><b> Nativization Conventions </b><br/><br/> The following nativization conventions are automatically applied to the Chakma output to increase readability. <br/> <ul> <li> /y/ and /áº/ are contextually placed based on the following rules. /y/ is used word-intially. Otherise, /áº/ is used at intervocalic and post-consonantal positions.',
        'Devanagari': `<b>Prishtamatra Orthography</b><br/><br/> In this type of orthography, /e/ vowel sign is written before a consonant. For instance, <span class="devanagari">à¤•à¥ à¤•à¥à¤¾ à¤•à¥à¥‡ à¤•à¥à¤¾à¥‡</span> instead of  <span class="devanagari">à¤•à¥‡ à¤•à¥‹ à¤•à¥ˆ à¤•à¥Œ</span>.<br/><br/> <b> Vowel à¥² </b> <br/><br>
        This letter is used instead of à¤ in the Marathi language and some Hindi orthographies. You can enable an option to output this letter instead of the usual à¤.
        <br/><br/> <b> Styles of Devanagari </b>  <br/><br/>
        There are several styles of Devanagari. You can choose which style you want to display the text.
        The Uttara style uses <a href="https://www.ashtangayoga.info/philosophie/sanskrit-und-devanagari/fonts-schriften-fuer-devanagari-und-lautschrift-iso-15919/devanagari/">Uttara</a>, Balbodh <a href="https://www.ashtangayoga.info/philosophie/sanskrit-und-devanagari/fonts-schriften-fuer-devanagari-und-lautschrift-iso-15919/devanagari/">Chandas</a> font, Nepali <a href="https://www.ashtangayoga.info/philosophie/sanskrit-und-devanagari/fonts-schriften-fuer-devanagari-und-lautschrift-iso-15919/devanagari/">Siddhanta-Nepli</a> font and Jain <a href="https://ektype.in/font-family/jaini.html">Ektype Jaini</a> font.
        <br/><br/> <b> Schwa Deletion </b> <br/><br/> In Hindi, Schwa is not explicitly deleted and must be done by the reader based on context. Aksharamukha uses some heuristics and renders the Schwa deleted text, if the associated option is enabled. The rules are described below: <br/> <ul><li>Schwa is removed from the final syllable. à¤®à¤¹à¤¾à¤¯à¤¾à¤¨ : mahÄyÄn. <ul><li> However, it is retained for monosyllabic words. à¤¨ : na. </ul><li> Schwa is removed from the second syllable in a Trisyllabic words that ends with a vowel other than â€˜aâ€™. à¤¸à¤¬à¤¸à¥‡ : sabse. <ul><li> But it is retained if the final syllable is a conjunct. à¤µà¤¸à¤¨à¥à¤¤à¥€ : vasantÄ«.</ul> <ul><li> It is also retained if the final syllable already has its Schwa deleted. à¤¨à¤¿à¤•à¤² : nikal.</ul> <li>For tetrasyllabic words, Schwa is removed from the second syllable, e.g à¤¬à¤¾à¤¤à¤šà¥€à¤¤ â€“ bÄtcÄ«t <ul><li> The penultimate Schwa is removed if the final syllable ends with a vowel other than /a/ e.g à¤—à¥à¤œà¤¼à¤°à¤¨à¥‡ : guzarne</ul> <ul><li> Schwa is retained if the second syllable is a conjunct. à¤¸à¤‚à¤ªà¥à¤°à¤¦à¤¾à¤¯ : sampradÄy </ul> <li> Schwa is not deleted in words that have more than four syllables. These tend to be compound words and would need lexical lookup to perform the correct deletion.</ul> A sample Hindi passage with Schwa deletion enabled is shown below.  <br/><br/> à¤¬à¥Œà¤¦à¥à¤§ à¤§à¤°à¥à¤® à¤­à¤¾à¤°à¤¤ à¤•à¥€ à¤¶à¥à¤°à¤®à¤£ à¤ªà¤°à¤®à¥à¤ªà¤°à¤¾ à¤¸à¥‡ à¤¨à¤¿à¤•à¤²à¤¾ à¤§à¤°à¥à¤® à¤”à¤° à¤¦à¤°à¥à¤¶à¤¨ à¤¹à¥ˆ à¥¤ à¤‡à¤¸à¤•à¥‡ à¤ªà¥à¤°à¤¸à¥à¤¥à¤¾à¤ªà¤• à¤®à¤¹à¤¾à¤¤à¥à¤®à¤¾ à¤¬à¥à¤¦à¥à¤§ à¤¶à¤¾à¤•à¥à¤¯à¤®à¥à¤¨à¤¿ (à¤—à¥Œà¤¤à¤® à¤¬à¥à¤¦à¥à¤§) à¤¥à¥‡ à¥¤ à¤µà¥‡ à¤›à¤ à¤µà¥€à¤‚ à¤¸à¥‡ à¤ªà¤¾à¤à¤šà¤µà¥€à¤‚ à¤¶à¤¤à¤¾à¤¬à¥à¤¦à¥€ à¤ˆà¤¸à¤¾ à¤ªà¥‚à¤°à¥à¤µ à¤¤à¤• à¤œà¥€à¤µà¤¿à¤¤ à¤¥à¥‡ à¥¤ à¤‰à¤¨à¤•à¥‡ à¤—à¥à¤œà¤¼à¤°à¤¨à¥‡ à¤•à¥‡ à¤…à¤—à¤²à¥‡ à¤ªà¤¾à¤à¤š à¤¶à¤¤à¤¾à¤¬à¥à¤¦à¤¿à¤¯à¥‹à¤‚ à¤®à¥‡à¤‚, à¤¬à¥Œà¤¦à¥à¤§ à¤§à¤°à¥à¤® à¤ªà¥‚à¤°à¥‡ à¤­à¤¾à¤°à¤¤à¥€à¤¯ à¤‰à¤ªà¤®à¤¹à¤¾à¤¦à¥à¤µà¥€