        'Grantha': 'The Grantha Nukta is a very modern addition to the Grantha script. It has been used to extend the native reportoire. Noto Sans Grantha has a few bugs but by and large the text should be properly rendered. <br/><br/> You can also toggle between the old-style /au/ sign <span class="grantha">ğ‘Œ•ğ‘Œ</span> and the new-style one <span class="grantha">ğ‘Œ•ğ‘—</span>. <br/><br/><b> Prakrit Orthography </b> <br/> When writing Prakrit, Grantha uses the Anusvara as a geminate marker and uses an alternate anusvara above to mark nasalization. <span class="grantha">ğ‘Œ¬ğ‘ğ‘Œ‚ğ‘Œ§ğ‘Œ€ ğ‘Œ¸ğ‘Œ°ğ‘Œ£ğ‘Œ€ ğ‘Œ—ğ‘Œ‚ğ‘Œ›ğ‘Œ¾ğ‘Œ®ğ‘Œ¿</span> as opposed to <span class="grantha">ğ‘Œ¬ğ‘ğ‘Œ¦ğ‘ğ‘Œ§ğ‘Œ‚ ğ‘Œ¸ğ‘Œ°ğ‘Œ£ğ‘Œ‚ ğ‘Œ—ğ‘Œšğ‘ğ‘Œ›ğ‘Œ¾ğ‘Œ®ğ‘Œ¿</span><br/><br/><b>Old-Style Final forms</b><br/>Pre-modern Grantha sometimes used final forms for other consonants similar to <span class="grantha">ğ‘Œ¤ğ‘</span> /t/, <span class="grantha">ğ‘Œ¨ğ‘</span> /n/ & <span class="grantha">ğ‘Œ®ğ‘</span> /m/ regularly used in Modern Grantha. <br/><br/><i>New Style:</i> <span class="grantha">ğ‘Œ…ğ‘Œ•ğ‘ ğ‘Œ…ğ‘Œ—ğ‘ ğ‘Œ…ğ‘Œ™ğ‘ ğ‘Œ…ğ‘Œšğ‘ ğ‘Œ…ğ‘Œœğ‘ ğ‘Œ…ğ‘Œğ‘ ğ‘Œ…ğ‘ŒŸğ‘ ğ‘Œ†ğ‘Œ¡ğ‘ ğ‘Œ…ğ‘Œ£ğ‘ ğ‘Œ…ğ‘Œ¤ğ‘ ğ‘Œ…ğ‘Œ¦ğ‘ ğ‘Œ…ğ‘Œ¨ğ‘ ğ‘Œ…ğ‘Œªğ‘ ğ‘Œ…ğ‘Œ¬ğ‘ ğ‘Œ…ğ‘Œ®ğ‘ ğ‘Œ…ğ‘Œ¯ğ‘ ğ‘Œ…ğ‘Œ°ğ‘ ğ‘Œ…ğ‘Œ²ğ‘ ğ‘Œ…ğ‘Œµğ‘ ğ‘Œ…ğ‘Œ¶ğ‘ ğ‘Œ…ğ‘Œ·ğ‘ ğ‘Œ…ğ‘Œ¸ğ‘ ğ‘Œ…ğ‘Œ¹ğ‘</span><br/><i>Old Style:</i> <span class="granthalig">ğ‘Œ…ğ‘Œ•ğ‘ ğ‘Œ…ğ‘Œ—ğ‘ ğ‘Œ…ğ‘Œ™ğ‘ ğ‘Œ…ğ‘Œšğ‘ ğ‘Œ…ğ‘Œœğ‘ ğ‘Œ…ğ‘Œğ‘ ğ‘Œ…ğ‘ŒŸğ‘ ğ‘Œ†ğ‘Œ¡ğ‘ ğ‘Œ…ğ‘Œ£ğ‘ ğ‘Œ…ğ‘Œ¤ğ‘ ğ‘Œ…ğ‘Œ¦ğ‘ ğ‘Œ…ğ‘Œ¨ğ‘ ğ‘Œ…ğ‘Œªğ‘ ğ‘Œ…ğ‘Œ¬ğ‘ ğ‘Œ…ğ‘Œ®ğ‘ ğ‘Œ…ğ‘Œ¯ğ‘ ğ‘Œ…ğ‘Œ°ğ‘ ğ‘Œ…ğ‘Œ²ğ‘ ğ‘Œ…ğ‘Œµğ‘ ğ‘Œ…ğ‘Œ¶ğ‘ ğ‘Œ…ğ‘Œ·ğ‘ ğ‘Œ…ğ‘Œ¸ğ‘ ğ‘Œ…ğ‘Œ¹ğ‘</span><br/><br/>There is an option to manually enable this.',
        'GranthaPandya': 'Aksharamukha uses a hack-encoded font that uses Malayalam characters to represent the Pandya Grantha characters. Medieval Grantha does not have its own Unicode block yet. As a result, the font has minor issues. For instance, the Repha will not be rendered properly in Chrome (or any other systems using HarfBuzz). You may want to use Uniscribe supporting programs like MS Word to properly render the text.',
        'Gujarati': 'Avestan <span class="avestan">ğ¬²</span> is rendered as <span class="gujarati">à«¹</span>. You can also enable an option to remove shwas that appear word finally. /bhautika/ àª­à«Œàª¤àª¿àª•  : /bhautik/',
        'Javanese': 'Aksharamukha places the repha automatically on the preceding consonants. /karma/ : <span class="javanese">ê¦ê¦‚ê¦©</span>.',
        'Kannada': 'As the only South-Indic script to have a native Nukta, it has been utilized to extend the script and create new characters. <br/><br/> <b> Nativization Conventions </b> <br/><br/>The following nativization conventions are automatically applied to the Kannada output to increase readability. <br/> <ul> <li> Pure nasal consonants are replaced by Anusvara when followed by their plosive counterparts. à²—à²™à³à²—à²¾ â†’ à²—à²‚à²—à²¾ <li>  Word-final consonantal /m/ is replaced by Anusvara. à²—à²®à³ â†’ à²—à²‚',
        'Kharoshthi': 'The vowel-length indicator is a pretty late feature. Kharoshthi in its earlier stages did not have it. The Segoe UI Historic font in Windows 10 supports a greater range of ligatures than <a href="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/googlei18n/noto-fonts/phaseIII_only/unhinted/otf/NotoSansKharoshthi/NotoSansKharoshthi-Regular.otf">Noto Sans Kharoshthi</a>. If you do not see various Kharoshthi ligatures, it is possibly because of the lack of Segoe Historic UI in your system and Noto Sans Kharoshthi is being used as the replacement web font. ',
        'Khudawadi': 'The Nukta has been used to extend the alphabet to represent /á¹£/, South-Indic consonants and the North-Indic Perso-Arabic consonants.',
        'Lepcha': 'There is no Virama and only few consonants have a final vowelless form. Hence, consonants without a final form are approximated to those with final forms. /buddha/ is approximated to /butdha/ <span class="lepcha">á°“á°ªá°³á°Œ</span> since final /t/ exists.',
        'Mahajani': 'Mahajani is sort of alphabetic and vowels can have multiple readings. Refer to Script Source and the Unicode proposal for more information.',
        'Modi': 'Modi usually does not distinguish between long and short /u/ and /i/. /u/ and /Å«/ are both represented by /u/ and, similarly, /i/ and /Ä«/ by /Ä«/. It also approximates the vocalic vowels /á¹›/, /á¹/, /á¸·/ and /á¸¹/ to /rÄ«/ & /lÄ«/. Aksharamukha by default applies this convention to the converted output. To disable this, please select \'preserve source\'',
        'Multani': 'Multani is more-or-less an Abjad with vowels being only explicitly shown in monosyllabic words and at word-initial positions. Otherwise, vowels are not represented. Aksharamukha applies this by default. If you would like to show vowels at all positions, please enable \'preserve source\'.',
        'Khmer': 'Khmer Repha is formed by default. /dharma/ :: <span class="khmer">á’á˜áŸŒ </span>',
        'Saurashtra': 'The aspirated versions of /n/, /m/, /l/ and /r/ are automatically formed using the \'Haaru\'. nha mha lha rha :: <span class="saurashtra">ê¢¥ê¢´ ê¢ªê¢´ ê¢­ê¢´ ê¢¬ê¢´</span>. This can be disabled by enabling <i> Preserve source </i>. <br/><br/><span class="saurashtra">/ê¢’ê£„â€ê¢°/</span> conjuncts is automatically formed for /ká¹£a/.  <br/><br/><b> Avagraha </b> <br/> Since Saurashtra does not have a native Avagraha, the Telugu Avagraha has been borrowed as it fits harmoniously in terms of shape into the script. <br/><br/><b> Saurashtra Haaru in Tamil </b><br/> When writing Saurashtra in Tamil, the sign Haaru that indicates aspiration of /n/, /m/, /l/ and /r/ is written as a colon. Thus, <span class="saurashtra">ê¢¥ê¢´ê¢·</span> is usually rendered as <span class="tamil">/à®¨à¯€:/</span>. Aksharamukha does not do this by default and it is usually rendered as <span class="Tamil">/à®¨à¯à®¹à¯€/</span>. If one requires the colon to denote aspiration, this can be enabled manually as an extra option - <i>Convert Saurashtra Haaru as :</i>',
        'Siddham': 'Siddham uses several alternate forms for the vowels /i/, /Ä«/ and /u/ and vowel sign /u/ and /Å«. /i/ has two variants <span class="siddham">ğ‘—˜</span> and <span class="siddham">ğ‘—™</span>, /Ä«/ has a variant form <span class="siddham">ğ‘—š</span> and /u/ has a variant form<span class="siddham">ğ‘—›</span>. Vowel signs /u/ and /Å«/ have a variant each, <span class="siddham">ğ‘—œ </span> and <span class="siddham">ğ‘—</span>. These variants can be enabled by choosing the appropriate option in the converter. <br/><br/> There are also several Devanagari-encoded Siddham fonts (see <a href="https://github.com/MihailJP/Muktamsiddham">here</a> and <a href="http://siddham.shikisokuzekuu.net/">here</a>), which can be enabled if required.',
        'Sharada': 'The Nukta has been used to extended the alphabet to represent Perso-Arabic and South-Indic characters. The Sharada vowels <span class="sharada">ğ‘†ƒá³ ğ‘†„á³ ğ‘†á³® ğ‘†ƒá³¯ ğ‘†ƒá³˜ ğ‘†ƒá³•</span> and their corresponding vowel signs <span class="sharada">ğ‘†‘á³ ğ‘†‘ğ‘†³á³ ğ‘†‘á³® ğ‘†‘á³¯ ğ‘†‘á³˜ ğ‘†‘á³•</span> are newly invented characters meant to be the Sharada equivalents of the following Devanagari characters <span class="devanagari">à¤ à¤‘ à¤ à¤’ à¥¶ à¥· à¤•à¥… à¤•à¥‰ à¤•à¥† à¤•à¥Š à¤•à¥– à¤•à¥—</span>. They have not been encoded in Unicode yet.<br/><br/>If you would like enter Kashmiri-specific vowels, please try <a href="https://satisarsharada.appspot.com">https://satisarsharada.appspot.com</a>.',
        'SylotiNagri': 'There doesn\'t seem to be a proper agreed way to create Syloti Nagri conjuncts. As a result, Noto Sans SylotiNagri does not form any proper conjuncts. See <a href="https://github.com/googlei18n/noto-fonts/issues/998">here</a>.',
        'TaiTham': 'Aksharamukha does the following automatically<br/><ul><li> Mai Kang Lai is automatically substituted for consonantal /á¹…/ in the preceeding consonant. saá¹…gho â†’ <span class="taitham">á©ˆá©˜á¨¥á©®á©£</span><li>Tall /a/ is used for /va/, /da/, /dha/ & /ga/. bhagavÄ â†’ <span class="taitham">á¨½á¨£á©…á©¤</a> <li> /ssa/ is rendered with <span class="taitham">á©” </span></ul>. <br/>Some fonts create the tall form of -Ä automatically without it being explictly chosen. The explicit choice of Tall -Ä can be disabled to allow such fonts to choose the appropriate form implicitly. <br/><br/><b>Mai Kain Lao after consonanant</b><br/><br/>If you select the option to place Mai Kang Lai on the succeeding consonant instead of the preceeding consonant, depending on the font this might may not work for vowel signs such as -Ä, -o, and -au. The font might place the sign on top of the vowel sign instead of the consonant. As in: <span class="taitham"> á©ˆá¨¥á©˜ </span> but <span class="taitham">á©ˆá©‰á©®á©£á©˜</span>. This appears to be a font issue. The font should ideally skip the vowel sign and place it directly on top of the consonant. ',
        'LaoTham': 'Aksharamukha does the following automatically<br/><ul><li> Mai Kang Lai is automatically substituted for consonantal /á¹…/ in the preceeding consonant. saá¹…gho â†’ <span class="laotham">á©ˆá©˜á¨¥á©®á©£</span><li>Tall /a/ is used for /va/, /da/, /dha/ & /ga/. bhagavÄ â†’ <span class="laotham">á¨½á¨£á©…á©¤</a> <li> /ssa/ is rendered with <span class="laotham">á©” </span></ul>. <br/>Some fonts create the tall form of -Ä automatically without it being explictly chosen. The explicit choice of Tall -Ä can be disabled to allow such fonts to choose the appropriate form implicitly.<br/><br/><b>Mai Kain Lao after consonanant</b><br/><br/>If you select the option to place Mai Kang Lai on the succeeding consonant instead of the preceeding consonant, depending on the font this might may not work for vowel signs such as -Ä, -o, and -au. The font might place the sign on top of the vowel sign instead of the consonant. As in: <span class="laotham"> á©ˆá¨¥á©˜ </span> but <span class="laotham">á©ˆá©‰á©®á©£á©˜</span>. This appears to be a font issue. The font should ideally skip the vowel sign and place it directly on top of the consonant.',
