        'KhuenTham': 'Aksharamukha does the following automatically<br/><ul><li> Mai Kang Lai is automatically substituted for consonantal /á¹…/ in the preceeding consonant. saá¹…gho â†’ <span class="khuentham">á©ˆá©˜á¨¥á©®á©£</span><li>Tall /a/ is used for /va/, /da/, /dha/ & /ga/. bhagavÄ â†’ <span class="khuentham">á¨½á¨£á©…á©¤</a> <li> /ssa/ is rendered with <span class="khuentham">á©” </span></ul>. <br/>Some fonts create the tall form of -Ä automatically without it being explictly chosen. The explicit choice of Tall -Ä can be disabled to allow such fonts to choose the appropriate form implicitly.<br/><br/><b>Mai Kain Lao after consonanant</b><br/><br/>If you select the option to place Mai Kang Lai on the succeeding consonant instead of the preceeding consonant, depending on the font this might may not work for vowel signs such as -Ä, -o, and -au. The font might place the sign on top of the vowel sign instead of the consonant. As in: <span class="khuentham"> á©ˆá¨¥á©˜ </span> but <span class="khuentham">á©ˆá©‰á©®á©£á©˜</span>. This appears to be a font issue. The font should ideally skip the vowel sign and place it directly on top of the consonant.',
        'Tamil': '<b> Superscripted Tamil </b> <br/>Tamil has a deficient script compared to other Indic scripts as it lacks distinct characters for many voiced and aspirated consonants. Publishers ha/d to resort to the use of superscript (and sometimes subscript) numerals to represent these letters in Tamil. <br/><br/><b> Nativization Conventions </b><br/><br/> The following nativization conventions are automatically applied to the Tamil output to increase readability. <br/> <ul> <li>Anusvara and Chandrabindu are replaced by the corresponding nasal consonant if followed by a plosive. <span class="tamil">à®šà®®à¯Ê¼à®¤Â³</span> â†’ <span class="tamil">à®šà®¨à¯à®¤Â³</span> <li>Intervocalic /à®¨/ is replaced by /à®©/. <span class="tamil">à®®à®¨à®¸à®¾</span> â†’ <span class="tamil">à®®à®©à®¸à®¾</span></ul><!--<b> Medieval e/o with Pulli </b><br/><br/> As a Brahmi-derived script, Tamil did not have atomic glyphs for short /e/ and short /o/ (as Brahmi was originally devised for Prakrit, which lacked them phonemically). Therefore, the Tamil Virama \'Pulli\' was used a vowel-length reducer. This was the case for around two millenia it was changed sometime around the 1700\'s. You can enable this option and choose to display this orthography. <br/><br/> Ä• Å ke kÅ : à® à®’ à®•à¯‡ à®•à¯Š (Medieval) : à®à¯ à®’à¯ à®•à¯†à¯ à®•à¯†à¯à®¾ (Modern)<br/><br>--> <b>Old Orthography</b><br/>The Tamil script was reformed in 1978 to normalize the script and remove some ligatured syllables. The following ligatured syllables were reformed to their respective non-ligatured forms. <br/><br/> <i>Old orthography:</i> <span class="tamilold">à®©à¯ˆ à®£à¯ˆ à®²à¯ˆ à®³à¯ˆ à®©à®¾ à®£à®¾ à®±à®¾</span><br/> <i>New orthography:</i> <span class="tamil">à®©à¯ˆ à®£à¯ˆ à®²à¯ˆ à®³à¯ˆ à®©à®¾ à®£à®¾ à®±à®¾</span> (New) <br/><br/> This can be enabled as an option. <a href="https://www.fontsc.com/font/lohit-tamil-classical">Lohit Tamil Classical</a> supports the old orthography. <br/><br/> <b>Contextual à®³</b><br/>Tamil (and South Indian Sanskrit fort tha matter) sometimes uses the retroflex /l/ à®³ for classical Sanskrits words. For instance, <span class="tamil">à®ªà¯à®°à®µà®¾à®³</span> /pravÄlÌ¤a/, <span class="tamil">à®ªà¯à®°à®³à®¯</span> /pralÌ¤aya/, <span class="tamil">à®¨à®¾à®®à®¾à®µà®³à®¿</span> /nÄmÄvalÌ¤i/ for classical sanskrit words <i>pravÄla</i>, <i>pralaya</i> and <i>nÄmÄvali</i>. This can be enabled in the converter. Few simples rules of thumbs are used to predict the appearance of the retroflex l. However, as of now this is an experimental feature.<br/><br/><b> Tamil Transcription </b><br/>Tamil has a very phonemic orthography and as such the orthographic does not accurately represent the pronunciation of the text. Consonants have multiple values based on their positionn in the word based on following simple rules of the thumb. Note that it might not work for non-native words, which tend to retain their original prounciation. <br/> <ul><li> Intervocalic /k/, /á¹­/, /t/ and /p/ and post-nasal plosives /k/, /c/, /á¹­/, /t/ and /p/ are replaced by their voiced counterparts. e.g. à®¨à®•à®®à¯ /nakam/ : /nagam/ <li> Word-initial and intervolic /c/ is replaced by /s/. à®šà®¨à¯à®¤à¯ˆ /cantai/ : /sandai/ <li> à®±à¯à®±à¯ /á¹Ÿá¹Ÿ/ and à®©à¯à®±à¯ /á¹‰á¹Ÿ/ are replaced by /á¹­r/ and /á¹‡á¸r/<br/><br/></ul> Sample Text: <br/><br/> <span class="tamil">à®•à¯†à®Ÿà®¿à®² à®†à®±à¯à®±à®¿à®©à¯ à®µà®Ÿà®•à®°à¯ˆà®¯à®¿à®²à¯ à®µà®¿à®³à®™à¯à®•à¯à®®à¯ à®¤à®¿à®°à¯à®µà®¤à®¿à®•à¯ˆ à®à®©à¯à®©à¯à®®à¯ à®µà¯€à®°à®Ÿà¯à®Ÿà®¾à®©à®¤à¯ à®¤à®¿à®°à¯à®ªà¯à®ªà®¤à®¿à®¯à®¿à®²à¯ à®‰à®•à®¨à¯à®¤à¯†à®´à¯à®¨à¯à®¤à®°à¯à®³à®¿à®¯à®¿à®°à¯à®•à¯à®•à¯à®®à¯ à®¤à®²à¯ˆà®µà®©à¯‡! à®¯à®¾à®©à¯ à®‡à®ªà¯à®ªà®¿à®±à®ªà¯à®ªà®¿à®²à¯ à®à®©à¯ à®…à®±à®¿à®µà¯ à®…à®±à®¿à®¯à®ªà¯ à®ªà®² à®•à¯Šà®Ÿà¯à®à¯ à®šà¯†à®¯à®²à¯à®•à®³à¯ˆà®šà¯ à®šà¯†à®¯à¯à®¤à¯‡à®©à®¾à®• à®à®©à®•à¯à®•à¯à®¤à¯ à®¤à¯‹à®©à¯à®±à®µà®¿à®²à¯à®²à¯ˆ. à®…à®µà¯à®µà®¾à®±à®¾à®•à®šà¯ à®šà¯‚à®²à¯ˆà®¨à¯‹à®¯à¯, à®¯à®¾à®°à¯à®•à¯à®•à¯à®®à¯ à®¨à¯‹à®¯à¯à®®à¯à®¤à®²à¯ à®ªà¯à®²à®ªà¯à®ªà®Ÿà