        'Sinhala': '<b> Sanskrit/Pali Orthography in Sinhala </b> <br/><br/> When Sinhala is used to write Sanskrit/Pali text, sometimes the short e/o are used to represent the Sanskrit long e/o. For instance, <span class="sinhala">à¶±à¶¸à·œ à¶·à¶œà·€à¶­à·™</span> instead of <span class="sinhala">à¶±à¶¸à· à¶·à¶œà·€à¶­à·š</span> <br/><br/><b> Conjuncts </b> <br/><br/> Modern Sinhala does not extensively use conjuncts except for /ká¹£a/ and the post-base forms of /ya/ (as in /kya/: <span class="sinhala">à¶šà·Šâ€à¶º</span>) and /ra/ (as in /kra/: <span class="sinhala">à¶šà·Šâ€à¶»</span>). Aksharamukha forms these automatically. However, older texts, particularly for Pali/Sanskrit, extensively used conjuncts and Repha. For instance, <span class="sinhala">à·ƒà¶¸â€à·Šà¶¸à·à·ƒà¶¸â€à·Šà¶¶à·”à¶¯à·Šâ€à¶°à·ƒâ€à·Šà·ƒ</span> instead of <span class="sinhala">à·ƒà¶¸à·Šà¶¸à·à·ƒà¶¸à·Šà¶¶à·”à¶¯à·Šà¶°à·ƒà·Šà·ƒ</span>. Notice the use of conjoining conjuncts such as <span class="sinhala">à¶¯à·Šâ€à¶°</span> and touching letters such as <span class="sinhala">à·ƒâ€à·Šà·ƒ</span>. Also, <span class="sinhala">à¶°à¶»à·Šâ€à¶¸</span> instead of <span class="sinhala">à¶°à¶»à·Šà¶¸</span>. This can be enabled by selecting \'enable all conjuncts\' as an option. <br/><br/> With the both of the above options enabled, the above example Pali verse will be rendered as: <br/><br/> <span class="sinhala">à¶ºà·™ à¶°à¶¸â€à·Šà¶¸à· à·„à·™à¶­à·”à¶´â€à·Šà¶´à¶·à·€à· à¶­à·™à·ƒà¶‚ à·„à·™à¶­à·”à¶‚ à¶­à¶®à·à¶œà¶­à·œ à¶†à·„ . <br/> à¶­à·™à·ƒà¶¤à·Šâ€à¶  à¶ºà·œ à¶±à·’à¶»à·œà¶°à·œ à¶‘à·€à¶‚ à·€à·à¶¯à·“ à¶¸à·„à·à·ƒà¶¸à¶«à·œ ..</span> <br/><br> And the Sanskrit text as: <br/><br/> <span class="sinhala">à¶…à¶±à·’à¶»à·œà¶°à¶¸à·Š à¶…à¶±à·”à¶­â€à·Šà¶´à·à¶¯à¶¸à·Š à¶…à¶±à·”à¶ â€à·Šà¶¡à·™à¶¯à¶¸à·Š à¶…à·à·à·â€à·Šà·€à¶­à¶¸à·Š . <br/> à¶…à¶±à·™à¶šà·à¶»à·Šâ€à¶®à¶¸à·Š à¶…à¶±à·à¶±à·à¶»à·Šâ€à¶®à¶¸à·Š à¶…à¶±à·à¶œà¶¸à¶¸à·Š à¶…à¶±à·’à¶»à·Šâ€à¶œà¶¸à¶¸à·Š .. <br/> à¶ºà¶ƒ à¶´à·Šâ€à¶»à¶­à·“à¶­à·Šâ€à¶ºà·ƒà¶¸à·”à¶­â€à·Šà¶´à·à¶¯à¶‚ à¶´à·Šâ€à¶»à¶´à¶¤à·Šâ€à¶ à·œà¶´à·à¶¸à¶‚ à·à·’à·€à¶¸à·Š . <br/> à¶¯à·™à·à¶ºà·à¶¸à·à·ƒ à·ƒà¶‚à¶¶à·”à¶¯à·Šâ€à¶°à·ƒâ€à·Šà¶­à¶‚ à·€à¶±à·Šâ€à¶¯à·™ à·€à¶¯à¶­à·à¶‚ à·€à¶»à¶¸à·Š ..</span>',
        'TamilExtended': 'An attempt in a printed publication to employ this system is shown below as used in the text called <a href="http://www.archive.org/stream/bhojacharitrama00sastgoog">Bhojacharitram</a>, published in 1916. <br/><img src="../statics/Grantha_Pulli.jpg"><br/> <span class="tamilextended">à´ªàµà´°à´¾à´°àµà´§àµà´¯à´¨àµà´¤à´¸àµà´¯ à´¨à´¾à´¶à´àµ à´š <br/>à´®àµà´àµà´œà´ƒ à´¸à´®àµà´•àµà´·àµ€à´¯à´¤à´¾à´®à´¿à´¤à´¿ à¥¥ <br/> à´µà´¿à´˜àµà´¨àµ‡à´¶à´àµ à´¸ à´®à´¹àµ‡à´¶à´àµ à´š à¥¤ <br/> à´¹à´°à´¿à´®àµ à´¨à´—à´°à´µà´¾à´¸à´¿à´¨à´ƒ <br/> à´¨à´¦àµ€à´ªà´°àµà´µà´¤ à´®à´¾à´¸àµ‡à´¦àµà´ƒ <br/>à´µà´¿à´ªàµà´°à´¾ à´¦àµ‡à´¶à´¾à´¨àµà´¤à´°à´®àµ à´¯à´¯àµà´ƒ à¥¥</span> <br/> <br/>prÄrdhyantasya nÄÅ›aÃ± ca <br/>muÃ±jaá¸¥ samká¹£Ä«yatÄmiti .. <br/>vighneÅ›aÃ± sa maheÅ›aÃ± ca . <br/>harim nagaravÄsinaá¸¥ <br/>nadÄ«parvata mÄseduá¸¥ <br/>viprÄ deÅ›Äntaram yayuá¸¥ ..<br/><br/> A <a href="https://groups.google.com/d/msg/mintamil/tDwV_UwYJKc/AVCkX2KQFV4J">commentary</a> on the Jaina Epic Nilakesi published in 1936 also uses this technique intermittently to disambiguate Sanskrit words that will otherwise be ambigous in the Tamil script, along with the proper Grantha script for Sanskrit quotations. There also been other recent publications that employed this method to print Sanskrit.<br/><br/><b>Ligated u & Å«</b><br/> Normally, when Grantha consonants are subsumed under Tamil orthography, they do not use ligating signs to represent the vowels u & Å« in consonants. However, this results increasing the horizontal space and insufficient visual harmony with the Tamil script, whose consonants usually take a ligating form for the vowels. Therefore, we have innovated Tamil-style ligation for Grantha consonants, hoping that they will be blending in harmoniously with the Tamil script <br/><br/> <i> Non-Ligated </i> <span class="tamilextended"><br>à´–àµ à´–àµ‚ à´—àµ à´—àµ‚ à´˜àµ à´˜àµ‚ à´›àµ à´›àµ‚ à´àµ à´àµ‚ à´ àµ à´ àµ‚ à´¡àµ à´¡àµ‚ à´¢àµ à´¢àµ‚ à´¥àµ à´¥àµ‚ à´¦àµ à´¦àµ‚ à´§àµ à´§àµ‚ à´«àµ à´«àµ‚ à´¬àµ à´¬àµ‚ à´­àµ à´­àµ‚</span>. <br/><br/><i> Ligated Style </i> <br/><span class="tamilextended"> à´–â€àµ à´–â€àµ‚ à´—â€àµ à´—â€àµ‚ à´˜â€àµ à´˜â€àµ‚ à´›â€àµ à´›â€àµ‚ à´â€àµ à´â€àµ‚ à´ â€àµ à´ â€àµ‚ à´¡â€àµ à´¡â€àµ‚ à´¢â€àµ à´¢â€àµ‚ à´¥â€àµ à´¥â€àµ‚ à´¦â€àµ à´¦â€àµ‚ à´§â€àµ à´§â€àµ‚ à´«â€àµ à´«â€àµ‚ à´¬â€àµ à´¬â€àµ‚ à´­â€àµ à´­â€àµ‚</span><br/><br/>The spacing signs are in wide-spread use for the Tamilized Grantha consonants <span class="tamilextended">à´œ à´¶ à´· à´¸ à´¹ à´•àµà´· à´¶àµâ€à´°</span>. However, in order to be symmetric, ligated forms have been innovated for them as well.<br/><br/><i> Non-Ligated </i> <span class="tamilextended"><br>à´œàµ à´œàµ‚ à´¶àµ à´¶àµ‚ à´¸àµ à´¸àµ‚ à´·àµ à´·àµ‚ à´¹àµ à´¹àµ‚ à´¶àµâ€à´°àµ à´¶àµâ€à´°àµ‚ à´•àµà´·àµ à´•àµà´·àµ‚</span><br/><br/><i> Ligated Style </i> <br/><span class="tamilextended"> à´œâ€àµ à´œâ€àµ‚ à´¶â€àµ à´¶â€àµ‚ à´¸â€àµ à´¸â€àµ‚ à´·â€àµ à´·â€àµ‚ à´¹â€àµ à´¹â€àµ‚ à´¶àµâ€à´°â€àµ à´¶àµâ€à´°â€àµ‚ à´•àµà´·â€àµ à´•àµà´·â€àµ‚</span><br/><br/>Users can choose the appropriate ligation style from the options.<br/><br/>You can read about the Agastya fontset <a href="http://www.virtualvinodh.com/projects/agastya">here</a>.',
        'Thaana': 'Aksharamukha automatically uses Ş‡Ş° to denote gemination. When Ş‡Ş° appears as a glottal stop (at the end of words), it is denoted using Ê”. The Arabic-specific characters in Thaana are approximated to their closest Indic counterparts. <br/><br/><b>Archaic /á¹‡/ </b><br/><br/> The archaic /á¹‡/ Ş± is only used when the <i>Preserve source</i> option is enabled, else it is replaced by /n/ Ş‚ by default.',
        'MeeteiMayek': 'Aksharamukha uses final consonants where available and resorts to using the explicit Virama for others. <br/><br/><b> Archaic Orthography </b> <br/><br/> Historically, Meetei Mayek had characters for the following: Ä« Å« aá¸¥ cha Ã±a á¹­a á¹­ha á¸a á¸ha á¹‡a Å›a á¹£a :: <span class="meeteimayek">ê¯‘ê«« ê¯‘ê«¬ ê¯‘ê«µ ê«¢ ê«£ ê«¤ ê«¥ ê«¦ ê«§ ê«¨ ê«© ê«ª ê«ª</span>. But, they are not in vogue any more. By default, Aksharamukha does not use these characters. They are replaced by their closest approximations: i u ah ca na ta tha da dha na sa sa :: <span class="meeteimayek">ê¯ ê¯ ê¯‘ê¯ê¯­ ê¯† ê¯… ê¯‡ ê¯Š ê¯— ê¯™ ê¯… ê¯ ê¯</span>. The historic characters are used only if the <i>preserve script</i> option is enabled.',
        'Malayalam': 'Chillus are formed automatically based on context in the output text.  /dharma/ becomes <span class="malayalam">à´§àµ¼à´®</span> according to Malayalam orthographic conventions and not <span class="malayalam">à´§à´°àµà´®</span><br/><br/>By default, Chillus in the input Malayalam text are not explicitly marked in the output script. To show Chillus in the converted text, enable <i>Show Chillus</i> in the input section. Chillus will then be shown followed by a Ë in the target script. <span class="malayalam">/à´§àµ¼à´®/</span> : dharËma <br/><br/> <b> Nativization Conventions </b> <br/><br/>The following nativization conventions are automatically applied to the Malayalam output to increase readability. <br/> <ul> <li> Pure nasal consonants and Anusvara are placed contextually. veá¹ƒkaá¹­a : <span class="malayalam">à´µàµ‡à´™àµà´•à´Ÿ</span> but gaá¹…gÄ : <span class="malayalam">à´—à´‚à´—à´¾</span> <li>  Word-final consonantal /m/ is replaced by Anusvara. </ul> <br/> <b> Traditional Orthography </b> <br/><br/> Switches to a web font that supports Traditional orthography. <span class="malayalamold">à´µà´¸àµà´¤àµ</span> instead of <span class="malayalam">à´µà´¸àµà´¤àµ</span>. The font (Meera) used for the traditional orthography can be downloaded from <a href="https://github.com/virtualvinodh/aksharamukha/blob/master/aksharamukha-front/src/statics/Meera-Regular.ttf">here</a>. <br/><br/> <b> Prakrit Orthography </b> <br/><br/> When writing Prakrit, Malayalam uses the Anusvara as a geminate marker and uses an alternate anusvara above to mark nasalization. <span class="malayalamold">à´¬àµà´‚à´§à´€ à´¸à´°à´£à´€ à´—à´‚à´›à´¾à´®à´¿ </span> as opposed to <span class="malayalam">à´¬àµà´¦àµà´§à´‚ à´¸à´°à´£à´‚ à´—à´šàµà´›à´¾à´®à´¿</span> <br/><br/> <b> Archaic II and AU </b> <br/><br/> Old Malayalam used <span class="malayalam">àµŸ à´•àµŒ</span> instead of <span class="malayalam">à´ˆ à´•àµ—</span> <br/><br/> <b> Dot Reph </b> <br/><br/> Pre-script reform Malayalam used a Repha instead of the /ra/ Chillu before consonants. <span class="malayalam">à´§àµà´®à´¾à´¯</span> instead of <span class="malayalam">à´§àµ¼à´®à´¾à´¯</span>',
        'PhagsPa': 'PhagsPa does not use conjuncts except for subjoined -r,-v- and -y. Instead, it splits the words in syllabic chunks of the forms - [C]V, [C]VC and CCV. Thus <i>samudgate</i> becomes <i>sa mud ga te</i> <span class="phagspa">ê¡› ê¡ê¡Ÿê¡Š ê¡‚ ê¡ˆê¡ </span>and <i>kleÅ›a</i> becomes <i>kle Å›a</i> <span class="phagspa">ê¡€ê¡™ê¡  ê¡š</span>. However, this leads to an ambiguity. A word like <span class="phagspa">ê¡›ê¡ˆ ê¡‹</span> can be read as <i>stana</i> or <i>satna</i> in the absense of the any vowel signs. <br/><br/> Aksharamukha converts the input text into syllabic chunks automatically and also reverses thep process for the transliteration from PhagsPa to other scripts. á ‚ U+1802 is used as the word separator in PhagsPa text.  <br/><br/> There are two styles of PhagsPa Script, Tibetan-styel and Seal Scrit-style as show below. These can be switched through options. The fonts for these versions can be downloaded from <a href="https://www.babelstone.co.uk/Fonts/Phags-pa.html">here</a>. <br/><br/> <b> Tibetan Style </b> <div class="phagspatib">ê¡³ê¡¡ á ‚ ê¡‹ ê¡ê¡¡ á ‚ ê¡ê¡Ÿê¡Š ê¡Šê¡œê¡– ê¡—</div> <br/><br/> <b> Seal Script Style <div class="phagspaseal">ê¡³ê¡¡ á ‚ ê¡‹ ê¡ê¡¡ á ‚ ê¡ê¡Ÿê¡Š ê¡Šê¡œê¡– ê¡—</div> <br/><br/></b> Windows 10 uses Microsoft PhagsPa to display the PhagsPa text. In the absence of this font, <a href="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/googlei18n/noto-fonts/phaseIII_only/unhinted/otf/NotoSansPhagsPa/NotoSansPhagsPa-Regular.otf">Noto Sans PhagsPa</a> is used to display the text.',
        'IPA': 'The IPA conversion is based on the normalized prescriptive pronunication expected from a Sanskrit text. This may not accurately reflect variations that usually occur based on the target script or even based on the region it is being read. It will for most part fail for scripts like Malayalam and Bengali as they have a phonemic orthography. <br/><br/> <b> Tamil </b> <br/><br/> For Tamil to IPA conversion, the results are mirrored from <a href="http://anunaadam.appspot.com">Anunaadam</a> which is far more accurate. <br/><br/> <b> Oriya </b> <br/><br/> The transcription follows the ruled provided <a href="https://github.com/OdiaWikimedia/Converter/blob/master/IPA-Romanization/ipa-roman">here</a> as Oriyan phonetics is a bit different to that of the other Indian languages such as the inherent vowel being /É”/ instead of /É™/.',
        'Telugu': ' <b> New Telugu characters </b> <br/><span class="telugu">à°´</span> is a historic Telugu letter that is equivalent to Tamil à®´. And Telugu also has it own Candrabindu character <span class="telugu">à°…à°€</span>. Being new characters, your Telugu font may not adequately support these characters. Please use an updated font to view these characters. <br/><br/> <b> Nativization Conventions </b> <br/>The following nativization conventions are automatically applied to the Telugu output to increase readability. <br/> <ul> <li> Pure nasal consonants are replaced by Anusvara when followed by their plosive counterparts. <span class="telugu">à°—à°™à±à°—à°¾ â†’ à°—à°‚à°—à°¾</span> <li>  Word-final consonantal /m/ is replaced by Anusvara. <span class="telugu">à°—à°®à± â†’ à°—à°‚</span></ul><b>Telugu Repha (Valapala Gilaka)</b><br/>In Pre-Modern Telugu, it was common to use a reph-sign (called <i>Valapala Gilaka</i>) for pre-consonantal /r/. For instance, <span class="telugu">à°§à°°à±â€à°®</span> (c.f Modern Kannada <span class="kannada">à²§à²°à³à²®</span>) as opposed to the modern <span class="telugu">à°§à°°à±à°®</span>. This can be manualy enabled if required. However, this only works with Noto Sans Telugu.<br/><br/><b>Telugu phonemes Ã¦ & Ç£</b><br/>The phonemes /Ã¦/ and /Ç£/ do exist in Telugu phonology but do not have orthographically distinct forms. For instance, the syllable /Ã¦/ is usually represented as <span class="telugu">à°•à±†â€‹</span> /kÄ•/ or <span class="telugu">à°•à±à°¯à°¾</span> /kyÄ/. However, Telugu linguists tend to use an underine beneath /Ä•/ and /e/ to unambiguously represent /Ã¦/ and /Ç£/ as in <span class="telugu">à°à¥’â€‹ à°•à±†à¥’</span> & <span class="telugu">à°à¥’â€‹ à°•à±‡à¥’â€‹</span>. You can see more about this in <a href="http://www.unicode.org/L2/L2020/20120-telugu-underline.pdf">L2/20-120</a>. Extrapolating this, the phoneme /Ã´/ is represented as /o/ with underline <span class="telugu">à°’à¥’â€‹ à°•à±Šà¥’â€‹</span>.<br/><br/><b>Tamil-Style letters</b><br/>When transcribing Tamil, sometimes, specifically in SriVaishnava literature, it is common to see Tamil-style glyphs for /<span class="telugu">à°´</span>/ and /<span class="telugu">à°±</span>/. You can read in detail about this specific orthographic practice in <a href="http://www.unicode.org/L2/L2020/20119-two-telugu-letters.pdf">L2/20-119</a>. For instance, the following Tamil verse could be transcribed as follows: <br/><br/><span class="tamil">à®¤à¯‚à®®à®£à®¿ à®®à®¾à®Ÿà®¤à¯à®¤à¯à®šà¯ à®šà¯à®±à¯à®±à¯à®®à¯ à®µà®¿à®³à®•à¯à®•à¯†à®°à®¿à®¯, <br/>à®¤à¯‚à®ªà®™à¯ à®•à®®à®´à®¤à¯ à®¤à¯à®¯à®¿à®²à®£à¯ˆà®®à¯‡à®²à¯ à®•à®£à¯à®µà®³à®°à¯à®®à¯<br/>à®®à®¾à®®à®¾à®©à¯ à®®à®•à®³à¯‡! à®®à®£à®¿à®•à¯à®•à®¤à®µà®®à¯ à®¤à®¾à®´à¯ à®¤à®¿à®±à®µà®¾à®¯à¯;<br/>à®®à®¾à®®à¯€à®°à¯! à®…à®µà®³à¯ˆ à®à®´à¯à®ªà¯à®ªà¯€à®°à¯‹? à®‰à®®à¯à®®à®•à®³à¯à®¤à®¾à®©à¯<br/>à®Šà®®à¯ˆà®¯à¯‹? à®…à®©à¯à®±à®¿à®šà¯ à®šà¯†à®µà®¿à®Ÿà¯‹ à®…à®©à®¨à¯à®¤à®²à¯‹?<br/>à®à®®à®ªà¯ à®ªà¯†à®°à¯à®¨à¯à®¤à¯à®¯à®¿à®²à¯ à®®à®¨à¯à®¤à®¿à®°à®ªà¯ à®ªà®Ÿà¯à®Ÿà®¾à®³à¯‹?<br/>à®®à®¾à®®à®¾à®¯à®©à¯, à®®à®¾à®¤à®µà®©à¯, à®µà¯ˆà®•à¯à®¨à¯à®¤à®©à¯ à®à®©à¯à®±à¯†à®©à¯à®±à¯<br/>à®¨à®¾à®®à®®à¯ à®ªà®²à®µà¯à®®à¯ à®¨à®µà®¿à®©à¯à®±à¯‡à®²à¯‹ à®°à¯†à®®à¯à®ªà®¾à®µà®¾à®¯à¯.</span> <br/><br/> <span class="teluguzha">à°¤à±‚à°®à°£à°¿ à°®à°¾à°¡à°¤à±à°¤à±à°šà± à°šà±à±˜à±à±˜à±à°‚ à°µà°¿à°³à°•à±à°•à±†à°°à°¿à°¯,<br/>à°¤à±‚à°¬à°™à± à°—à°®à°´à°¤à± à°¤à±à°¯à°¿à°²à°£à±ˆà°®à±‡à°²à± à°•à°£à±à°µà°³à°°à±à°‚<br/>à°®à°¾à°®à°¾à°¨à± à°®à°—à°³à±‡! à°®à°£à°¿à°•à±à°•à°¦à°µà°‚ à°¤à°¾à°´à±à°¤à°¿à°±à°µà°¾à°¯à±;<br/>à°®à°¾à°®à±€à°°à±! à°…à°µà°³à±ˆ à°à°´à±à°ªà±à°ªà±€à°°à±‹? à°‰à°®à±à°®à°—à°³à±à°¦à°¾à°¨à±<br/>à°Šà°®à±ˆà°¯à±‹? à°…à°‚à°¡à±à°°à°¿à°šà± à°šà±†à°µà°¿à°¡à±‹ à°…à°¨à°‚à°¦à°²à±‹?<br/>à°à°®à°ªà± à°ªà±†à°°à±à°‚à°¦à±à°¯à°¿à°²à± à°®à°‚à°¦à°¿à°°à°ªà± à°ªà°Ÿà±à°Ÿà°¾à°³à±‹?<br/>à°®à°¾à°®à°¾à°¯à°¨à±, à°®à°¾à°¦à°µà°¨à±, à°µà±ˆà°—à±à°‚à°¦à°¨à± à°à°‚à°¡à±à°°à±†à°‚à°¡à±à°°à±<br/>à°¨à°¾à°®à°‚ à°ªà°²à°µà±à°‚ à°¨à°µà°¿à°‚à°¡à±à°°à±‡à°²à±‹ à°°à±†à°‚à°¬à°¾à°µà°¾à°¯à±.</span><br/><br/>This can be enabled using the appropriate options. Also, it is necessary to enable Tamil transcription in the input section, in case you are transcribing directly from the Tamil script. You also need to use <a href="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/virtualvinodh/aazhvaar-telugu/AazhvaarTelugu.otf">Aazvhvaar Telugu</a> font to display the Tamil-style letters properly. Without the font, the letters will appear as <span class="telugu">à°´</span> & <span class="telugu">à±˜</span>.',
        'Tibetan': 'The Sanskrit phonemes /c/, /ch/, /j/ and /jh/ are mapped to consonants TSA, TSHA, DZA and DZHA, respectively (according to Tibetan conventions). This can be changed by selecting the <i>Use Sanskrit palatals</i> options, which will use the Sanskrit-specific consonants <span class="tibetan">à½… à½† à½‡ à½‡à¾·</span> instead of <span class="tibetan">à½™ à½š à½› à½œ</span> . <br/><br/> Tibetan Mark TSA-PHRU is used as the Nukta. /yya/, /rya/, /rva/ and /vva/ are indicated using the full-subjoined forms as <span class="tibetan">à½¡à¾», à½ªà¾», à½ªà¾º, à½à¾º</span>. Also, <span class="tibetan">à½</span> is replaced with /jhÌˆa/ and <span class="tibetan">à½ </span> with /a/. <span class="tibetan">à¼ˆ</span> and <span class="tibetan">à¼ˆ</span> become Dandas. <br/><br/> <b> Dbu-Med Style </b> <br/><br/> You can also enable to choose the Dbu-Med style for displaying Tibetan instead of the usual Dbu-Can style. Aksharamukha uses the Qomolangma-Betsu font from <a href="http://www.yalasoo.com/English/docs/yalasoo_en_font.html">here</a>.  <br/><br/> <span class="tibetan">à½¨à½¼à½¾à¼‹à½“à¼‹à½˜à½¼à¼‹à½–à½´à¼‹à½‘à¾¢à½±à¼‹à½¡</span> (Dbu-Can) <br/> <span class="tibetandbumed">à½¨à½¼à½¾à¼‹à½“à¼‹à½˜à½¼à¼‹à½–à½´à¼‹à½‘à¾¢à½±à¼‹à½¡</span> (Dbu-Med) <br/><br/> <b> Nativization Conventions </b> <br/><br/> The following nativization conventions are automatically applied to the Tibetan output in according with Tibetan orthographic practices. <br/> <ul> <li> /va/ is replaced by /ba/ at intervocalic positions and if followed by consonantal /r/ </li> <li>Spaces are replaced by Tshegs à¼‹</li> <li> Explicit Virama is not shown </li><ul>',
        'Brahmi': 'The Segoe UI Historic font in Windows 10 supports a greater range of ligatures than <a href="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/googlei18n/noto-fonts/phaseIII_only/unhinted/otf/NotoSansBrahmi/NotoSansBrahmi-Regular.otf">Noto Sans Brahmi</a>. If you do not see various Brahmi ligatures, it is possibly because of the lack of Segoe Historic UI in your system and Noto Sans Brahmi is being used as the replacement web font.',
        'Kaithi': 'Devanagari numerals have been used as Kaithi seems to lack a numeral set of its own. Devanagari Avagraha has been borrowed for the same reason as well. U+2E31 is used as the word separator. The Nukta has been used to extend the alphabet to represent the South-Indic consonants and the North-Indic Perso-Arabic consonants.',
        'Vatteluttu': 'Vatteluttu is not yet enocoded in Unicode. Aksharamukha uses a hack-encoded font that uses the Tamil block to encode Vatteluttu. It does not contain /j/, /Å›/, /á¹£/, /s/ and /h/ (as in Modern Tamil) in its reportoire as Grantha letters were usually augmented with Vatteluttu characters to represent them',
        'Tirhuta': 'The Nukta was used to extend the characters to create equivalents of South-Indic and other Nukta-ted characters that typically occur in North Indic scripts.',
        'Takri': 'Devanagari Avagraha has been used to denote Avagraha in Takri as well. The Nukta was used to extend the characters to create equivalents of South-Indic and other Nukta-ted characters that typically occur in North Indic scripts. <br/><br/><b>Medieval Takri</b><br/>In Medieval Takri, /kha/ can stand for both /á¹£a/ and /kha/ depending on the context. This can be enabled by selecting the appropriate option. <br/><br/> <b> Consonant Gemination </b> <br/> In Takri orthography, the gemination of consonants is not usually written. Thus /uttara/ is usually written as <span class="takri"> ğ‘š„ğ‘š™ğ‘š¤ </span> /utara/ and not <span class="takri">ğ‘š„ğ‘š™ğ‘š¶ğ‘š™ğ‘š¤</span> /uttara/. This can be manually enabled as well.',
        'Urdu': 'Urdu is an abjad. It amounts to short-vowels being not written and /v/ and /y/ also denoting long vowels. (The following assumes the consonants have an inherent /a/ like Indic scripts for illustration.). In the absense of short vowels, /ava/ can stand for /va/, /Å«/, /o/ or /au/, /aya/ can stand for /ya/, /Ä«/, /e/ or /ai/. On the same note /kava/ could be /kava/, /kÅ«/, /ko/, /kau/ and /kaya/ could be /kaya/, /kÄ«/, /ke/ or /kai/, Thus /kayarala/ probably should be read /kerala/ and /hayadarÄbÄd/ as /haidarÄbÄd/. Additionally, the short-vowels (i/u) have to be guessed by context. As in North-Indic scripts, the Schwa deletion is also not shown explicitly. Ideally, /urdÅ«/ should be written as /Ø§ÙØ±Ù’Ø¯ÙÙˆ/ but it is often written as /Ø§Ø±Ø¯Ùˆ/ (aradava). One should know that the first vowel is a short /u/, the schwa /a/ in r is deleted, and /va/ in this case denotes /Å«/. Thus giving the reading <s>a</s><sup>u</sup>r<s>a</s>d<s>(ava)</s><sup>Å«</sup>. /Ù…ÛŒÚº/ (mayaá¹ƒ) must be read m<s>(aya)</s><sup>e</sup>á¹ƒ /meá¹ƒ/, /ÛÙ†Ø¯ÙˆØ³ØªØ§Ù†/ (hanadavasatÄna) is read h<s>a</s><sup>i</sup>n<s>a</s>d<s>(ava)</s><sup>Å«</sup>s<s>a</s>tÄn<s>a</s> /hindÅ«stÄn/.<br/><br/> Aksharamukha approximates the Arabic-specific consonants to their nearest Indic counterparts and Hamza is shown with an underscore. Ayin is mapped to /a/. Fathatan becomes just an /n/. <br/><br/> If your Urdu text does not show vowel marks, please select the appropriate option to get the proper output. In this way, Aksharamukha assumes all consonants have an inherent /a/ and the Mater Lectionis i.e. /v/ and /y/ are rendered as consonants. The reader has to guess the appropriate reading based on context (as shown above).',
        'Tagalog': 'In Phillippine scripts, /i/ denotes both /i/ and /e/ and /u/ denotes both /u/ and /o/. Some Tagalog fonts have a character for /r/ but it is not officially encoded in Unicode.',
        'Tagbanwa': 'In Phillippine scripts, /i/ denotes both /i/ and /e/ and /u/ denotes both /u/ and /o/.',
        'Buhid': 'In Phillippine scripts, /i/ denotes both /i/ and /e/ and /u/ denotes both /u/ and /o/.',
        'Hanunoo': 'In Phillippine scripts, /i/ denotes both /i/ and /e/ and /u/ denotes both /u/ and /o/.',
        'Sundanese': '<b> Archaic Orthography </b> <br/><br/> Sundanese had characters for the following: á¹›, á¸· and bha :: <span class="sundanese">á®» á®¼ á®½</span>, but they are not in vogue any more. By default, Aksharamukha does not use these characters. They are replaced by their closest approximations: reu, leu and ba :: <span class="sundanese">á®›á®© á®œá®© á®˜</span>. The archaic characters are used only if the <i>preserve script</i> option is enabled. <br/><br/> <b>Archaic Conjuncts</b> <br/><br/> Sundanese also had subjointed version of ma and wa, and also final-consonantal form for /k/ and /m/. For instance, <span class="sundanese">á®Šá®¬ /kma/,  á®Šá®­ /kva/, á®ƒá®¾ /ak/, á®ƒá®¿ /am/ </span> as opposed to <span class="sundanese"> á®Šá®ªá®™, á®Šá®ªá®, á®ƒá®Šá®ª and á®ƒá®Šá®ª.</span>This can be manually enabled in the coverter.<br/><br/>',
        'Limbu': '<b> Mukhphreng and Kemphreng </b><br/><br/> The Glottal Stop (Mukhphreng) is transliterated using Ê” and the Kemphreng (Vowel Lengthening Mark), when ocurring with vowels other than /i/ and /u/ is denoted by ê‰ U+A789.<br/><br/> <b> Historic Orthography </b> <br/><br/> Limbu had characters for the following: jha Ã±a á¹£a á¹ƒ :: <span class="limbu">á¤‰ á¤Š á¤š á¤²</span>, but they are not in vogue any more. By default, Aksharamukha does not use these characters. They are replaced by their closest approximations: ja na Å›a á¹… :: <span class="limbu">á¤ˆ á¤ á¤™ á¤±</span>. The historic characters are used only if the <i>preserve script</i> option is enabled. <br/><br/> <b>Limbu Devanagari Transliteration Convention</b> <br/><br/> Limbu has its own convention, when transliterating to Devanagari. It uses vowels with Nuktas and Visarga to denote the vowel-lengthening. For instance,  <span class="limbu"> á¤€á¤§ á¤€á¤¨ á¤€á¤§á¤º á¤á¤§ á¤á¤¨ á¤á¤§á¤º  </span> is transliterated as: <span class="limbudeva">à¤à¤¼ à¤“à¤¼ à¤à¤¼à¤ƒ à¤•à¥‡à¤¼ à¤•à¥‹à¤¼ à¤•à¥‡à¤¼à¤ƒ  </span> instead of à¤ à¤’ à¤ê‰ à¤•à¥† à¤•à¥Š à¤•à¥†ê‰. The above sample text would be rendered as <br/><br/> <span class="limbudeva">à¤†à¤™à¥à¤—à¤¾à¥½ à¤ªà¥‡à¤¨à¥à¤¸à¤ƒà¤¨à¥ à¤•à¥‡à¤¼à¤²à¤ƒà¤®à¥à¤¬à¤¾à¥½ à¤®à¤¨à¤¾à¤†à¥¥ à¤†à¤¹à¤¿à¤®à¥ à¤«à¥à¤™à¥à¤²à¥‡à¤¼à¤™à¥, à¤†à¤™à¥à¤—à¤¾à¥½ à¤†à¤¤à¥à¤¤à¤¿à¤¨à¥à¤¨à¤¾à¤™à¥ à¤¸à¤¾à¤®à¥â€Œà¤¯à¥‹à¤¨à¤¿à¤¬à¤¾, à¤¸à¤¾à¤®à¥â€Œà¤¯à¥‹à¤¥à¤¿à¤®à¥à¤¹à¤¾à¥½ à¤¨à¤¸à¤¾à¤ƒà¤¨à¥ à¤®à¥‡à¤¼à¤¨à¥à¤œà¥‹à¤•à¥à¤¨à¤¾à¤¬à¤¾ à¤†à¥¥ à¤¥à¤¿à¤•à¥â€Œà¤¯à¥‡à¤®à¥ à¤•à¤¿à¤ªà¥à¤®à¤¾ à¤•à¥‡à¤˜à¥à¤¬à¤¾ à¤¤à¥à¤•à¥à¤®à¤¾à¤²à¥à¤²à¥‡ à¤¯à¤¾à¤™à¥à¤¸à¤¾à¤™à¥, à¤¸à¤¿à¤¦à¤¾à¤¬à¤¾à¤™à¥à¤¦à¤¾à¥½ à¤®à¥‡à¤¼à¤¤à¥à¤›à¤¿à¤™à¥à¤¸à¥‡à¤¼ à¤ªà¥‡à¤—à¤¾à¤™à¥à¤¸à¤¾à¤™à¥ à¤®à¥‡à¤¼à¤¨à¥à¤¨à¥‚à¤¬à¤¾ à¤•à¤° à¤¯à¥‡à¤¼à¤¸à¥à¤®à¤¾à¤™à¥à¤“ à¤¨à¤¸à¤¾à¤¨à¥ à¤šà¤¾à¥‡à¤ƒà¤•à¥ à¤¹à¥‡à¤®à¥à¤¤à¥à¤™à¤¾à¤™à¥à¤§à¥‹ à¤†à¤™à¥à¤—à¤¾ à¤µà¥‡à¤¤à¥à¤¤à¤¾à¤™à¥ à¤¬à¤¾à¤°à¥‹à¥¥ - à¤²à¤¾à¤² à¤¬à¤¹à¤¾à¤¦à¥à¤° à¤²à¤¿à¤®à¥à¤¬à¥. à¤•à¤™à¥ à¤¨à¥à¤¸à¤¿à¤¯à¥‡à¤•à¥à¤ªà¤¾ à¤¯à¤¾à¤•à¥à¤ªà¤™à¥à¤—à¥‡à¤¼à¤®à¥à¤¬à¤¾ à¤¸à¥‡à¤¸à¥‡ à¤šà¥à¤®à¥à¤²à¥à¤™à¥ à¤•à¤¾à¤²à¥‡à¤®à¥à¤ªà¥‹à¤™à¥ à¤¬à¤¾ à¤šà¤‡à¤¤à¥â€Œà¤°à¥‹à¥¥ à¤†à¤²à¥à¤²à¤¬à¤¾ à¤¯à¥‡à¤¼à¤¤à¥à¤›à¤¿à¥½à¤—à¥‡à¤®à¥à¤ªà¤¾ à¤¸à¥‡à¤¸à¥‡ à¤šà¥à¤®à¥à¤²à¥à¤™à¥ à¥§à¥§ à¤…à¤•à¥à¤¤à¥à¤¬à¤° à¥¨à¥¦à¥§à¥ª à¤¸à¤¿à¤²à¤¿à¤—à¥à¤¦à¤¿ à¥«à¥¦à¥¦ à¤®à¤¨à¤¾à¤²à¤®à¥à¤®à¥‹ à¤ªà¤¾à¥‡à¤ƒà¤™à¥à¤² à¤ªà¤¤à¥à¤²à¥‹à¥¥</span><br/><br/>The converter applies this convention if this option is selected.  <br/><br/> <b>SAI-I for Vowel Legnth</b><br/><br/> Limbu has two orthographic conventions. One that uses the SA-I to denote vowel-lengthening and final-forms for the regular vowel - <span class="limbu">á¤á¤¢á¤´ /kun/ vs á¤á¤¢á¤á¤» /kÅ«n/</span>. In the latter, the vowel-lengthening is explicitly shown using Kemphreng - <span class="limbu">á¤á¤¢á¤´ /kun/ vs á¤á¤¢á¤ºá¤´ /kÅ«n/</span>. Aksharamukha by default uses the latter but you can also select the first orthography.',
        'Lao': 'Lao lacks several consonants required to accurately write Pali and therefore transliteration of Pali/Sanskrit is lossy with several inconsistent approximations. Non-Brahmic lao-specific consonants are sometimes used in transcribing Pali, particularly /àº”/, /àºš/, /àºŸ/ and  /àº®/. The first three are transliterated using the Nukta as /dÌˆ/, /pÌˆ/ and /bÌˆ/, and the last one is mapped to /á¹Ÿ/. As noted earlier, the conventions are pretty inconsistent. Sometimes, /àº”/ is used to mark gemination but other times it is indicated by plain duplication of consonants, even within the same text. For instance, <a href="http://www.watmai.com.au/373837713732375437693732374537713737.html">here</a> you find: <br/><br/> àº­àº´àº•àº´àº›àº´à»‚àºª  àºàº°àº„àº°àº§àº²  àº­àº°àº£àº°àº«àº±àº‡àºªàº±àº¡àº¡àº²àºªàº±àº¡àºàº¸àº—à»‚àº—  àº§àº´àºŠàºŠàº²àºˆàº°àº£àº°àº™àº°àºªàº±àº¡àº›àº±àº™à»‚àº™ àºªàº¸àº„àº°à»‚àº•  à»‚àº¥àºàº°àº§àº´àº—àº¹  àº­àº°àº™àº¸àº•àº•àº°à»‚àº£  àº›àº¸àº£àº´àºªàº°àº—àº±àº¡àº¡àº°àºªàº°àº£àº°àº–àºµ  àºªàº±àº•àº–àº²à»€àº—àº§àº°àº¡àº°àº™àº¸àºªàºªàº²àº™àº±àº‡<br/> itipiso bagavÄ arahaá¹…sammÄsambuddo vijjÄcaranasampanno sugato lokavidÅ« anuttaro purisadammasarathÄ« satthÄdevamanussÄnaá¹… <br/><br/> àº­àº´àº•àº´àº›àº´à»‚àºª àºàº°àº„àº°àº§àº² àº­àº°àº£àº°àº«àº±àº‡àºªàº±àº¡àº¡àº² àºªàº±àº¡àºàº¸àº”à»‚àº— àº§àº´àº”àºŠàº²àºˆàº²àº£àº°àº™àº°àºªàº±àº¡àº›àº±àº™à»‚àº™ àºªàº¸àº„àº°à»‚àº• à»‚àº¥àºàº°àº§àº´àº—àº¹ àº­àº°àº™àº¸àº” àº•àº°à»‚àº¥ àº›àº¸àº£àº´àºªàº°àº—àº±àº¡àº¡àº±àº”àºªàº°àº£àº°àº–àºµ àºªàº±àº”àº–àº²à»€àº—àº§àº°àº¡àº°àº™àº¸àº”àºªàº²àº™àº±àº‡  <br/> itipiso bagavÄ arahaá¹…sammÄ sambudÌˆdo vidÌˆjÄcÄranasampanno sugato lokavidÅ« anudÌˆ talo purisadammadÌˆsarathÄ« sadÌˆthÄdevamanudÌˆsÄnaá¹…  <br/><br/> On a similar note, /r/ and /l/ are sometimes mixed and /á¹Ÿ/ may be used for /r/ as in /àº®àº±àºàºªàº²/ (á¹ŸaksÄ). /pÌˆb/ is also used to denoted geminated /b/, apart from /bb/ as in /àºªàº±àºšà»€àº/ (sapÌˆbe) and /àºªàº±àºà»€àº/ (sabbe). And àº³ is occasionally also used to denote gemination of /m/ as in /àºªà»àº²àº¡àº²àºªà»àº²àºàº¸àº”à»‚àº—/ (sÄá¹ƒmÄsÄá¹ƒbudÌˆdo), which can be seen <a href="http://yarkhu.blogspot.com/2017/08/blog-post.html">here</a>. /cha/ is also replaced by /sa/ as in /àº„àº±àº”â€‹àºªàº²â€‹àº¡àº´/ (gacchÄmi) or / àº„àº±àºªàºªàº°àº¡àº´/ (gasami) or even /gacsami/ for /gacchÄmi/. àº /Ã±/ is used for both /Ã±/ and /y/ as in /Ã±akkha/ instead of /yakkha/ (Since /àº/ is technically cognate to brahmic /ya/ and only later came to represent /Ã±/ phonetically) and /kg/ can also represent /gg/. Refer <a href="http://www.pali.pratyeka.org/#Laoaccent">here</a> for more quirks of Laotian Pali  <br/><br/>Maha Sila Viravong made additiions to the Lao script to express Pali phonology properly and created a one-to-one correspondance with the Brahmic set of consonants. Please refer to Lao (Pali) for further information. <h5> Lao nativation </h5> The following are applied to the output based on the above Laotians conventions <br/><br/> 1. /cha/ is mapped to /sa/ <br/> 2. Both /ya/ and /Ã±a/ are mapped to /Ã±a/ (àº) <br/> 2. /dÌˆ/ is used to mark gemination for /d/, /t/, /th/ and /s/ <br/> 3. /pÌˆ/ is used as the gemination marker for /p/ and /b/',
        'LaoPali': 'The Buddhist Institute of Vientiane, using the expanded script, has published several books such as Dhammapada and Pali Grammar. Their aim was to make Pali more accessible to the common public. A few modern publications have been printed using the additiona characters in an attempt to propose an etymological orthography for Lao and make Pali accessible. Please refer to the Unicode <a href="https://www.unicode.org/L2/L2017/17106r-lao-for-pali.pdf">proposal</a> for further information. <br/><br/><b> Lao Orthography </b> <br/>This applies the following conventions: <br/> <ul><li> Replace Anusvara with /á¹…/ <li> Show the inherent /a/ explicitly </ul> The sample Pali text would be rendered as: <br/><br/> <span class="laopali"> à»€àº àº˜àº±àº¡àº¡àº² à»€àº«àº•àº¸àº›àº›àº°àº àº°àº§àº² à»€àº•àºªàº±àº‡ à»€àº«àº•àº¸àº‡ àº•àº°àº–àº²àº„àº°à»‚àº• àº­àº²àº«àº° àº¯ <br/> à»€àº•àºªàº±àºàºˆàº° à»‚àº àº™àº´à»‚àº£à»‚àº˜ à»€àº­àº§àº±àº‡ àº§àº²àº—àºµ àº¡àº°àº«àº²àºªàº°àº¡àº°à»‚àº“ </span> <br/><br/><b> Sajjhaya Orthography </b> <br/>Applies the Thai Sajjhaya orthographic conventions to the Lao text. See the <a href="http://aksharamukha.appspot.com/describe/Thai">Thai script</a> page for more details. The sample Pali text above would be renderd as: <br/><br/><span class="laopali">à»€àº àº˜àº±àº¡à»Œàº¡àº² à»€àº«àº•àº¸àº›à»Œàº›àº àº§àº² à»€àº•àºªà» à»€àº«àº•àº¸à» àº•àº–àº²àº„à»‚àº• àº­àº²àº« àº¯ <br/>à»€àº•àºªàº±àºà»Œàºˆ à»‚àº àº™àº´à»‚àº£à»‚àº˜ à»€àº­àº§à» àº§àº²àº—àºµ àº¡àº«àº²àºªàº¡à»‚àº“ àº¯àº¯</span><br/><br/><b>Sajjhaya Orthography (Nativized)</b><br/>This combines the features of Lao orthography and Sajjhaya orthography. Using this, the above text would be rendered as: <br/><br/><span class="laopali">à»€àº àº˜àº±àº¡à»Œàº¡àº² à»€àº«àº•àº¸àº›à»Œàº›àº°àº àº°àº§àº² à»€àº•àºªàº±àº‡ à»€àº«àº•àº¸àº‡ àº•àº°àº–àº²àº„àº°à»‚àº• àº­àº²àº«àº° àº¯<br/>à»€àº•àºªàº±àºà»Œàºˆàº° à»‚àº àº™àº´à»‚àº£à»‚àº˜ à»€àº­àº§àº±àº‡ àº§àº²àº—àºµ àº¡àº°àº«àº²àºªàº°àº¡àº°à»‚àº“ àº¯àº¯</span><br/><br/><b>Lao Phonetic</b><br/>This replaces the following consonants with the equivalent phonetic counterpart. <br/><br/> àº„ â†’ àº, àºŠ â†’ àºˆ, àº— â†’ àº”, àº â†’ àºš, Niggahita â†’ àº‡à». <br/> <br/>It also applies other diacritics such using combining breve and ring below to certain consonants as in the Thai Phonetic orthography. See Thai script page for more details.',
        'Thai': '<b> Thai Digraphs </b> <br/>Thai considers certain CC sequences as digraphs and treats them as indivisible units. Thus, /dve/ is written as à¹€à¸—à¸ºà¸§ as opposed to the usual à¸—à¸ºà¹€à¸§, with à¸—à¸ºà¸§ being a digraph. Aksharamukha follows the following rules of thumb to detect digraphs. <br/> <ul> <li> Word-inital clusters <li> Conjuncts with the semi-vowels ( /ya/, /va/, /ra/, /la/ ) in post-consonantal positions <li> Conjuncts of /h/ in both post-consonantal and pre-consonantal positions <li>Conjuncts of /s/ in pre-consonantal postions </ul> This digraph application is done by default to the output text. <br/> <br/><b> Thai Orthography </b> <br/>This applies the following conventions: <br/> <ul> <li> Replace Anusvara with /á¹…/ <li> Show the inherent /a/ explicitly <li> Digraphs are reversed </ul> The Sample pali text above would be rendered as: <br/><br/> <span class="thai"> à¹€à¸¢ à¸˜à¸±à¸¡à¸¡à¸² à¹€à¸«à¸•à¸¸à¸›à¸›à¸°à¸ à¸°à¸§à¸² à¹€à¸•à¸ªà¸±à¸‡ à¹€à¸«à¸•à¸¸à¸‡ à¸•à¸°à¸–à¸²à¸„à¸°à¹‚à¸• à¸­à¸²à¸«à¸° à¸¯ <br/> à¹€à¸•à¸ªà¸±à¸à¸ˆà¸° à¹‚à¸¢ à¸™à¸´à¹‚à¸£à¹‚à¸˜ à¹€à¸­à¸§à¸±à¸‡ à¸§à¸²à¸—à¸µ à¸¡à¸°à¸«à¸²à¸ªà¸°à¸¡à¸°à¹‚à¸“ à¹š </span> <br/><br/> <b> SajjhÄya Orthography </b> <br/>The <a href="https://www.sajjhaya.org/">Sajjhaya</a> edition of the Triptaaka uses a different kind of orthography. It follows the following conventions. <ul> <li> The Phinthu    à¸º  is replaced by Thanthakat     à¹Œ  (Except /à¸‡/ which is shown without any marks). /kittÄ«/: à¸à¸´à¸•à¹Œà¸•à¸µ</li> <li> Unless, the conjunct is combination of a varga (/ka/ to /ma/) and non-varga letter (/ya/ to /ha/), then it is replaced by Yamaka   à¹ and treat the sequence as a digraph. /dve/: à¹€à¸—à¹à¸§, /brÄhmaá¹‡a/: à¸à¹à¸£à¸²à¸«à¹à¸¡à¸“ </li> <li> Mark /a/ explicitly before conjuncts. /kamma/: à¸à¸±à¸¡à¹Œà¸¡ (Except digraphs: /tatra/ à¸•à¸•à¹à¸£)</li></ul> For instance <br/><i>evaá¹ƒ me sutaá¹ƒ, ekaá¹ƒ samayaá¹ƒ bhagavÄ bÄrÄá¹‡asiyaá¹ƒ viharati isipatane migadÄye tatra kho bhagavÄ paÃ±cavaggiye bhikkhÅ« Ämantesi: "dve me bhikkhave, antÄ pabbajitena na sevitabbÄ</i> <br/>à¹€à¸­à¸§à¹ à¹€à¸¡ à¸ªà¸¸à¸•à¹, à¹€à¸­à¸à¹ à¸ªà¸¡à¸¢à¹ à¸ à¸„à¸§à¸² à¸à¸²à¸£à¸²à¸“à¸ªà¸´à¸¢à¹ à¸§à¸´à¸«à¸£à¸•à¸´ à¸­à¸´à¸ªà¸´à¸›à¸•à¹€à¸™ à¸¡à¸´à¸„à¸—à¸²à¹€à¸¢ à¸•à¸•à¹à¸£ à¹‚à¸‚ à¸ à¸„à¸§à¸² à¸›à¸±à¸à¹Œà¸ˆà¸§à¸±à¸„à¹Œà¸„à¸´à¹€à¸¢ à¸ à¸´à¸à¹Œà¸‚à¸¹ à¸­à¸²à¸¡à¸±à¸™à¹Œà¹€à¸•à¸ªà¸´: "à¹€à¸—à¹à¸§ à¹€à¸¡ à¸ à¸´à¸à¹Œà¸‚à¹€à¸§, à¸­à¸±à¸™à¹Œà¸•à¸² à¸›à¸±à¸à¹Œà¸à¸Šà¸´à¹€à¸•à¸™ à¸™ à¹€à¸ªà¸§à¸´à¸•à¸±à¸à¹Œà¸à¸²<br/> <br/><b> Sajjhaya Orthography (Nativized)</b><br/> This combines the features of Thai orthography and Sajjhaya orthography. Using this, the above text would be rendered as: <br/>à¹€à¸­à¸§à¸±à¸‡ à¹€à¸¡ à¸ªà¸¸à¸•à¸±à¸‡, à¹€à¸­à¸à¸±à¸‡ à¸ªà¸°à¸¡à¸°à¸¢à¸±à¸‡ à¸ à¸°à¸„à¸°à¸§à¸² à¸à¸²à¸£à¸²à¸“à¸°à¸ªà¸´à¸¢à¸±à¸‡ à¸§à¸´à¸«à¸°à¸£à¸°à¸•à¸´ à¸­à¸´à¸ªà¸´à¸›à¸°à¸•à¸°à¹€à¸™ à¸¡à¸´à¸„à¸°à¸—à¸²à¹€à¸¢ à¸•à¸°à¸•à¹à¸£à¸° à¹‚à¸‚ à¸ à¸°à¸„à¸°à¸§à¸² à¸›à¸±à¸à¹Œà¸ˆà¸°à¸§à¸±à¸„à¹Œà¸„à¸´à¹€à¸¢ à¸ à¸´à¸à¹Œà¸‚à¸¹ à¸­à¸²à¸¡à¸±à¸™à¹Œà¹€à¸•à¸ªà¸´: "à¹€à¸—à¹à¸§ à¹€à¸¡ à¸ à¸´à¸à¹Œà¸‚à¸°à¹€à¸§, à¸­à¸±à¸™à¹Œà¸•à¸² à¸›à¸±à¸à¹Œà¸à¸°à¸Šà¸´à¹€à¸•à¸™à¸° à¸™à¸° à¹€à¸ªà¸§à¸´à¸•à¸±à¸à¹Œà¸à¸²<br/><br/><b> Thai Phonetic </b><br/>Thai Phonetic follows phonetic Thai spelling as shown <a href="https://www.sajjhaya.org/node/101">here</a>. The following conventions are applied <ol><li>Inherent /a/ is explicitly displayed<li>/ga/ and /ja/ are shown as <span class="thainative">à¸Ì¥ </span> /ka/ with ring below and <span class="thainative">à¸ˆÌ¥</span> /ca/ with ring below <li> /da/ & /ba/ are replaced by à¸” & à¸š <li> Anusvara and consonantal /á¹…/ is shown as à¸‡à¹. /maá¹…galaá¹ƒ/ : <span class="thainative">à¸¡à¸±à¸‡à¹à¸Ì¥à¸°à¸¥à¸±à¸‡à¹</span> <li> Conjuncts with /y/, /r/, /l/, /v/, /h/ are showing as a digraph with combining breve below. /dve/ : <span class="thainative">à¹€à¸”Íœà¸§</span> <li> /h/-initial conjuncts are also shown with a combining breve. /brÄhmaá¹‡a/ : <span class="thainative">à¸šÍœà¸£à¸²à¸«Íœà¸¡à¸°à¸“à¸°</spa