        'WarangCiti': '/h/ is sometimes used to denote vowel lengthening as in /ah/, /ih/ and /uh/. Given that the consonants have an inherent vowel and a functional Virama is not present, the lack of inherent vowel must be ascertained contextually (similar to Schwa deletion in Hindi). Likewise, consonantal clusters must also be read contextually.<br/><br/> <span class="warangciti">ğ‘£„</span> is actually the glottal stop /Ê”/ but seems to be traditionally mapped to Visarga. The digraph <span class="warangciti">ğ‘¢¹ğ‘£—</span> is mapped to /vÌˆ/ (v + nukta) <br/><br/> <b> Conservative Warang Citi </b><br/><br/> A form of conservative Warang Citi orthography used superscripted letters to indicate aspiration and conjuncts, thereby trying to compensate for the lack of a Virama. For instance, /ananta/ :: <span class="warangciti">ğ‘£ğ‘£“ğ‘£“â€ğ‘£•</span> (as opposed to <span class="warangciti">ğ‘£ğ‘£“ğ‘£“ğ‘£•</span>) or /Å«á¹­á¹­uÄ«/ <span class="warangciti">ğ‘£‡ğ‘£’â€ğ‘£’ğ‘£ƒğ‘£†</span> (as opposed to <span class="warangciti">ğ‘£‡ğ‘£’ğ‘£’ğ‘£ƒğ‘£†</span>). Without the visual clustering, the sequences could be read as /ananata/ (even /annata/ for that matter!) or /Å«á¹­aá¹­auÄ«/. The superscript just makes it explicit that the letters are to be read as a cluster. Similarly, aspirated consonants are shown using superscripted /h/, like /bha/ : <span class="warangciti">ğ‘£—â€ğ‘£™</span> and /cha/ : <span class="warangciti">ğ‘£â€ğ‘£™</span>. Also, /á¹ƒ/ is clustered with the previous vowel as in /aá¹ƒá¸e/ : <span class="warangciti">ğ‘£â€ğ‘£€ğ‘£‘ğ‘£ˆ</span>. The conservative orthography also used /á¹£/ : <span class="warangciti">ğ‘£</span>, whereas in modern orthography it would be simply replaced by /s/ : <span class="warangciti">ğ‘£</span>. <br/><br/>These are not enabled by default and only used when the <i>Preserve source</i> option is selected. Using this type of conservative orthography, the above Pali verse would be rendered as: <br/><br/> <span class="warangciti">ğ‘£…ğ