        'Newa': 'Newa used \'Murmered \'Consonants in its reportoire. These are atomically encoded in Unicode. If you select enable murmered consonants, the sequences /há¹…a/, /hÃ±a/, /hna/, /hma/ and /hra/ replaced by their atomic murmered equivalents <span class="newa">/ğ‘“/, /ğ‘™/, /ğ‘¤/, /ğ‘ª/ and /ğ‘­/</span> respectively. <br/><br/> Newa has two ways for forming r-initial conjuncts - one without repha /rka/: <span class="newa">ğ‘¬ğ‘‘‚â€ğ‘</span> and one with repha /rka/: <span class="newa">ğ‘¬ğ‘‘‚ğ‘</span>. Aksharamukha by default uses the repha-form, as it is the one used in Sanskrit texts. But this behavior can be changed by disabling the repha option. <br><br/> Newa also sometimes uses a special variant to form conjuncts of /ta/ usually before /ka/, /sa/ and /va/. <span class="newa">ğ‘Ÿğ‘‘‚ğ‘ ğ‘Ÿğ‘‘‚ğ‘³ ğ‘Ÿğ‘‘‚ğ‘° </span> (normal) :: <span class="newa">ğ‘Ÿğ‘‘‚â€ğ‘ ğ‘Ÿğ‘‘‚â€ğ‘³ ğ‘Ÿğ‘‘‚â€ğ‘°</span> (special). This can also be optionally enabled and it will form this special form for all conjuncts with initial /ta/. <br/><br/>  This Noto Sans Newa has few issues and may not display some conjuncts properly, in those cases you may want to use an alternate devanagar-encoded Newa font. It can be downloaded from <a href="https://github.com/virtualvinodh/aksharamukha/blob/master/aksharamukha-front/src/statics/Nepal-lipi.ttf">here</a>.',
        'Ranjana': 'Ranjana is not yet encoded in Unicode. As a result, all of the existing fonts are either legacy 8-bit fonts or Unicode fonts that have been hack-encoded to Devanagari or Tibetan.  Aksharamukkha uses a Devanagari-encoded Ranjana font as the default. In the absence of this font, the text will appear as plain Devanagari. <br/><br/> Ranjana being a pan-Indic script has several styles. There are two Tibetan styles, Lantsa and Wartu. These can be selected by enabling the respective option in the converter. These Tibetan-style fonts have been encoded in Tibetan Unicode and can be download from <a href="http://sonamdawa.com/download/#elf_l1_VGliZXRhbiBGb250cyAoVU5JQ09ERSkvTGFudHNhIGFuZCBXYXJ0dQ" target="_blank">here</a>. <br/><br> None of the fonts are perfect. Some complex ligatures like /trya/ etc. are better supported by the tibetan-style fonts rather than the default one. Please choose the font that displays your text the best.',
        'Wancho': '<b> Wancho Tones </b> <br><br/> Wancho tones can be formed as follows: ka\\_ ka\\- ka\\! ka\\; :: <span class="wancho">ğ‹”ğ‹ğ‹¬ ğ‹”ğ‹ğ‹­ ğ‹”ğ‹ğ‹® ğ‹”ğ‹ğ‹¯</span> <br/><br/> <b> Wancho Nasalized Vowels </b> <br/><br/>The Wancho nasalized vowels <span class="wancho">ğ‹¢ ğ‹£ ğ‹¤ ğ‹¥</span> are formed using the Anusvara as <i>oá¹ƒ Äá¹ƒ aá¹ƒ iá¹ƒ</i> and the other set of vowels <span class="wancho">ğ‹¦ ğ‹§ ğ‹¨ ğ‹ª</span> are formed using the Chandrbaindu as <i>omÌ emÌ ÄmÌ umÌ</i>. Apart from these vowels, the Anusvara is mapped to /á¹…/ and the Chandrabindu to /n/. <br/><br/> <b> Special Consonants </b><br/><br/>The special consonants <span class="wancho">ğ‹¡</span> /tr/ and <span class="wancho">ğ‹ </span> /ts/ are formed automatically from the sequences /tr/ and /ts/. And <span class="wancho">ğ‹’</span> /w/ as combination of /v/ and Nukta: /vÌˆ/.',
