        'Hebrew': `The mapping essentially follows traditional Hebrew phonology.
        <br/><br/>
        Hebrew is an Abjad that does not usually mark vowels using dedicated letters. In Hebrew, vowels may be optionally indicated using nikkud (dot). But they are usually eschewed in written Hebrew (particularly in Modern Hebrew texts). In the absence of such dots, all consonants (including the mater lectionis letters /v/ and /y/ used to denote vowels /e/, /o/ and /i/) will be transliterated with an inherent 'a'. The reader has to guess the correct vocalization based on context (much like <a href="/describe/Urdu">Urdu</a>). Thus, <span class="hebrew">×”×•×“×™</span> will be transliterated as /havadaya/. Ideally, it should be written with nikkud as <span class="hebrew"> ×”×•Ö¹×“Ö´×™</span>, which will be rightly rendered as /hodÄ«/. Please select the option <i>Vowels are not marked</i> if your text does not use any nikkud. <br/>
        <br/>
        Aksharamukha does differentiate between <i>shva na</i> and <i>shva nakh</i>. A shva is considered to be a <i>shva na</i> under the following conditions. <br/>
        <ul>
          <li>Under the first letter of a word</li>
          <li>If two shvas follow each other, the second schva if the letters are differrent</li>
          <li>If two shvas follow each other, the first schva if the letters are similar</li>
          <li>Under a letter with dagesh</li>
        </ul>
        In all the above cases, the schva was will transliterated as a short /e/ and any other schvas will be considered to denote vowelless consonants (<i>schva nakh</i>). e.g <span class="hebrew">×‘Ö°Ö¼×œÖ·×‘Ö·Ö¼×ª</span> is transliterated as /bÄ•labat/ and not /blabat/.
        Distinguishing schvas is very nuanced and these are just rules of thumb for the most common cases. This can be overridden to treat all shvas as <i>shva nakh</i> by selecting the appropriate option in the input text.<br/><br/>

        Characters are geminated using the dagesh. e.g. /mannÄ/ : <span class="hebrew">×Ö·× Ö¼Ö¸</span>. /k/ is geminated using /q/, since it already has a dagesh. Other characters containing a dagesh e.g /b/ are not geminated. Final letters (if they exist) are also appropriately used at word-final positions. (e.g) /malayÄlaá¹ƒ/ : <span class="hebrew">×Ö·×œÖ·×™Ö¸×œÖ·×Ö°</span><br/><br/>

        <b> Nativization </b> <br/>
        The following conventions are applied by default to make the text a bit more readable and in accordance with Hebrew orthography.
        <ul>
          <li> Shva nakh is removed at word-final positions. e.g. /ukÄl/ : <span class="hebrew">×Ö»×›Ö¼Ö¸×œ</span></li>
          <li> A word will not end with a vowel-bearing nikkud. It is always apppended by either <span class="hebrew">×</span> or <span class="hebrew">×”</span> depending on the vowel mark.  e.g. /nama/ : <span class="hebrew">× Ö·×Ö·×”</span></li>
          <li> To denote /v/, <span class="hebrew">×•</span> is used at the beginning of words and <span class="hebrew">×‘</span> at all other positions.  e.g. /vivÄha/ : <span class="hebrew">×•Ö´×‘Ö¸×”Ö·×”</span></li>
        </ul>
        You can disable the above and generate a more one-to-one transliteration by selecting the <i> Preserve source </i> option.
        <br/><br/>
        <b> Approximations </b> <br/>
        The following characters are approximated to their closest Indic counterparts as their counterparts to do not exist in many Indic scripts: <i>Ayin</i> to <i>Aleph</i>, <i>Tsadi</i> to <i>/ts/</i>, <i>Tav to Tet</i>, <i>Het</i> to <i>Kaf</i> and <i>Shin (with Sin dot)</i> to <i>Samekh</i>.
        The extra short <i>hataf</i> vowels are approximated to their regular short counterparts.
        <br/><br/>
        <b> Kamats Katan </b> <br/>
        Traditionally, <i>kamats katan</i> is the preferred nikkud used to denote short /o/. However, this is visually indistinguishable from the vowel dot <i>kamats gadol</i> that denotes /Ä/.
        Unicode has a distinct character U+05C7 Qamats Qatan to distinguish it from the character for <i>kamats gadol</i> U+05B8. However, in many cases, U+05B8 is used for both /Ä/ and /Å/.
        If you'd like to distinguish them in the input text, please use U+05C7 to explicitly mark <i>kamats katan</i>. <br/><br/>
        For transliteration purposes, the vowel dot <i>Holam</i> has been mapped to short /o/ to avoid the visual ambiguity in the output text. This is can be overridden to use U+05C7 by selecting the appropriate option. Also, if you would like <i>Holam</i> to be transliterated as a long /o/, an override for that is  available.
        <br/><br/>
        <b> Qof </b> <br/>
        The Indic /k/ is mapped to <span class="hebrew">×›Ö¼</span> and <span class="hebrew">×§</span> is mapped to /q/ reflecting traditional Hebrew pronunciation. However, Modern Hebrew tends to spell /k/ with Qof. This can be enabled by selecting the appropriate option.
